const HSA = "A photograph, unlike a memory, does not fade; and it is precisely this permanence that makes it treacherous. The remembered face softens and recomposes itself with each recollection, absorbing the moods of the rememberer until it becomes less a record than a companion. The photographed face, by contrast, is fixed at an instant the sitter did not choose and cannot revise. We imagine that the photograph preserves the past, but what it preserves is only a surface, severed from the duration that gave it meaning. To look at an old photograph is therefore to be confronted not with the past itself but with its irrecoverable exterior, and the melancholy peculiar to such images arises from this: they show us everything except the one thing we want, which is the continuance of the moment beyond its own border.";
const HSB = "It is fashionable to insist that, in a democracy, every opinion deserves equal weight. The principle is generous, but it conflates two things that ought to be kept apart: the equal right to hold an opinion and the unequal reliability of opinions once held. A citizen's right to a view on the safety of a bridge is indeed equal to an engineer's; the worth of their views, as guides to whether the bridge will stand, is not. To treat the two as identical is not to honour democracy but to abolish the very notion of expertise, and with it the possibility that some questions have answers at all. The democratic instinct is sound where it concerns ends, the values a society chooses to pursue; it becomes incoherent only when extended to means, the technical questions of how those ends might be reached.";
const HSC = "We speak of progress as though it were a single road leading in one direction, so that to move along it is necessarily to improve. But the metaphor flatters us. A society may grow richer while growing more anxious, more connected while growing lonelier, more capable while growing less wise. Each of these advances is real; none is illusory; yet their sum does not obviously point one way. The error lies in supposing that because we can measure some things, those are the things that matter, and that what eludes measurement may be safely ignored. A civilisation that mistakes its instruments for its purposes will keep its accounts impeccably and lose, without noticing, the very goods the accounts were meant to serve.";
const HSD = "What the Map Omits\n\nThe cartographer, who loved his country, drew\neach river truer than the rivers were,\nand where a marsh had drowned a hopeful road\nhe inked a firm intention through the blur.\n\nHis maps were beautiful. Men set their course\nby confident green meadows that, in fact,\nwere bog; and cursed, waist-deep, the careful hand\nthat drew the world it wished, and called it fact.\n\nYet who would keep the other kind of map,\nall honest swamp, no promise in the lines?\nWe ask of those who chart us, not the truth,\nbut somewhere firm to stand among the signs.";

const VH1 = `To say that we live in the present is to say less than we suppose, for the present we are given is never the bare point at which a note sounds, but a thickened now in which that note still trails the one before it and already leans toward the one to come. Strip away that fringe and the melody collapses into a succession of unrelated instants, none of which could be heard as music. What we call hearing a phrase, then, is not the adding of remembered notes to a present one, as though memory reached back to fetch them; it is rather that the just-elapsed is still given, sinking but not yet absent, while the not-yet is sketched in advance by the very shape of what we have heard. Consciousness does not occupy time as a body occupies a chair. It holds open a span within which alone there can be any object at all.`;
const VH2 = `Suppose that what makes you the same person tomorrow as today is not the persistence of a single substance, a soul or an unbroken body, but the holding-together of overlapping psychological connections: memories that reach back, intentions that reach forward, a character that bends only slowly. If so, identity admits of degree, and the question of whether some far future person will be you may have no sharp answer where the connections thin. The discomfort this produces is instructive. We had assumed that personal identity was the deep fact on which the rationality of self-concern rested, that I save for my old age because that pensioner will be me. But if identity is only the name we give to a sufficiently dense web of relations, then perhaps it was never identity that mattered, and what we owe our future selves we may owe, in lesser measure, to others to whom we are bound as well.`;
const VH3 = `Imagine a forgery so perfect that no instrument and no eye could tell it from the original: every crack in the varnish, every hesitation of the brush, reproduced. The puzzle is not whether we could detect the fraud but whether, undetected, it would be as good. Those who say it must be, since nothing perceptible distinguishes the two, assume that the value of a painting is exhausted by how it looks. Yet our experience of a work is not the experience of a coloured surface alone but of an achievement, a thing meant and made at a particular moment by a particular hand reaching beyond what had been done before. The forgery, however dazzling its surface, is parasitic: it reaches only toward another painting. To call the two equal is not to praise the copy but to forget what we were valuing in the original.`;
const HD1 = `I have always been, my sister says, the reasonable one, and I see no cause to dispute a description so obviously just. When our mother's house was to be divided, it was I who proposed that we each take what we valued and leave the rest to sober arithmetic; and if the few good pieces happened to be the ones I valued, that is hardly an argument against a fair principle. Clara wept, of course. Clara has always wept easily, which is its own kind of advantage, though I would never say so to her face. I contented myself with observing that sentiment is a poor basis for the settlement of an estate, and that one of us, at least, had kept her head.`;
const HD2 = `We kept the clock our grandfather had wound
long after it had any right to keep
the time; its hands, arrested, had not found
the hour in years, and yet we let it sleep

upon the shelf, as though to take it down
would be to grant the morning it had stopped.
A broken clock is honest twice; we frown
at honesty so seldom, and so opt

to keep the lie that something has not moved.
The stopped hands point, and what they point me to
is not a time at all, but time arranged
to spare us from the little that is true.`;
const HD3 = `The shelves groan with the memoirs of the successful, each pressing upon us the habits to which the author attributes a fortune: rise early, take the risk, trust the gut. The advice is delivered with the confidence of one who tried it and won. What the genre cannot show us, because they did not write books, are the many who rose just as early, took the same risk, trusted the same gut, and failed. Without them the sample is not merely incomplete; it is chosen by the very outcome it claims to explain. A habit shared by winners and losers alike explains nothing about winning, however vividly the winner remembers it.`;
const HD4 = `The new clerk had been blamed for the missing money, and I knew, as surely as I knew my own name, that he had not taken it, for I had seen the under-manager at the drawer myself. But the under-manager was a friend to my advancement, and the clerk was no one, and the words I might have said grew heavier the longer I held them, until they were too heavy to lift at all. I told myself I would speak if it came to dismissal. It came to dismissal. I found, when the moment arrived, that I had quietly revised the memory of what I had seen into something usefully uncertain, and I shook the young man's hand as he left, and wished him well, and meant it.`;
const MD1 = `Whenever Priya returned to the town she had grown up in, she was surprised to find it smaller, as though the years away had quietly let the air out of it. The main street she had thought grand was a single row of shops; the hill she had toiled up as a child she now climbed without noticing. She understood that the town had not shrunk, that it was she who had grown and gone and seen larger streets and steeper hills. And yet the disappointment was real, and it was not the town she missed but the child for whom the town had once been the whole of the world.`;
const MD2 = `The gardener plants the slow-grown oak
he knows he will not sit beneath,
and tends the sapling stroke by stroke
as one might tend a thing bequeathed.

He will not see the shade it throws
nor hear the noon birds in its crown;
he digs because the planter knows
the debt of every shade sat down.`;
const MD3 = `A study notes that towns with more bookshops have higher average lifespans and wonders aloud whether reading lengthens life. Before we shelve our medicines for novels, we might ask what sort of town can support a bookshop at all: one with disposable income, leisure, education and good clinics. Each of these bears on how long its residents live. The bookshop may be less the cause of the long life than a symptom of the same prosperity that buys the long life by other means.`;
const MD4 = `The old man fed the gulls each morning from the end of the pier, and the town had its opinions. Some said he was lonely; some said he was a nuisance, drawing vermin with wings; the children simply liked him. He said nothing to any of them. He had buried a wife who had loved the birds, and feeding them was neither loneliness nor nuisance but a conversation he was not ready to end, conducted in the only language still open to him.`;
const MD5 = `The pundit predicts a downturn within the next few years. If it comes, he is vindicated; if it does not, the few years have not yet elapsed. A forecast that no possible run of events could disconfirm tells us nothing about the world, though it may tell us a good deal about the forecaster, who has arranged to be right whatever happens. The test of a prediction is not whether it can come true but whether it could have come false.`;
const MD6 = `They paved the meadow for the cars
and named the road Meadow View,
as if a word set into tar
could keep a promise grass once knew.

The sign is honest, in its way:
it tells you what is not there now,
and every evening, come what may,
the traffic crawls where cattle used to bow.`;

const VH4 = `A college replaces the oars of its ancient boat one at a time as each splinters, until after a century not a single original timber remains, yet the club speaks without hesitation of the same boat that won a famous race before any living member was born. We are untroubled by this, and rightly, for the boat's sameness was never lodged in its particular planks but in the unbroken practice of repair that carried it forward. The difficulty arrives only when we turn the same reasoning on ourselves and find that we too have replaced almost every cell, and that what persists is likewise not a stuff but a continuity of upkeep. We resist the comparison because we would rather our own sameness rested on something we possess than on something we merely keep doing.`;
const VH5 = `I have given a great deal to my brother over the years, and I keep no ledger, as a smaller man might. When his business failed I took him in, and if I reminded him most mornings of the comfort of my spare room, it was only that he might feel the full warmth of what he had been given. I asked nothing in return but his acknowledgement, which he was strangely slow to offer, and a certain deference in the matter of the television, and the use of his car at weekends, and his silence when our mother asked which of her sons had been the steadier. He left in the spring without a word of thanks. Some people, I have found, cannot bear to be helped.`;
const VH6 = `We cut your name into the harbour stone
the summer that you left, and thought it fast,
as though the chisel's bite could hold alone
against the patient committee of the past.

The sea attends each evening, takes its share,
a letter at a time, and does not grieve;
by autumn there was less of you to spare,
by spring a groove the eye could half believe.

I come to trace it still with one cold thumb
and find I read the absence, not the name,
and cannot say, when all the letters come
to nothing, whether you are still the same.`;
const VH7 = `Two drivers leave the same party equally drunk and equally careless. One reaches home without incident; the other, on an identical road, meets a child who has wandered from a gate and cannot stop in time. We punish the second far more harshly, and we blame him more, though the only difference between them lies in what happened to cross their paths, which is to say in something neither chose nor controlled. Either our practice of blame is partly irrational, fastening on outcomes that luck decides, or else blame was never only a matter of the will, and the careless driver who kills has, by killing, become a different object of judgement from the one who merely might have. The uncomfortable thought is not that we should blame the lucky driver less, but that we may have no principled ground for blaming him less than we do.`;
const VH8 = `Mrs Carrow had a gift for putting people at their ease, and she exercised it on the young man from the north the moment he arrived, complimenting his jacket in a tone that somehow placed it, and asking after his mother's health with a warmth that reminded the table he had a mother who might be unwell. She drew him out on his work, repeating his answers to the others a little more slowly, as one hands round something unfamiliar so that everyone may have a look. By the fish course he had stopped volunteering anything, and she remarked, to the company at large, how shy the clever ones always were, and how she loved to coax them out.`;
const VH9 = `To translate a poem is to be told, politely, that you cannot. The argument runs that a poem's meaning is inseparable from the particular sounds and rhythms of its first language, so that to change the words is to make a different poem wearing the borrowed authority of the old one's name. There is force in this, but it proves too much, for by the same reasoning I could not read the original twice and find the same poem, since my second reading falls in a different silence than my first. What the objection mistakes is the assumption that a poem is a fixed object rather than a set of instructions for an experience, instructions a good translation reissues in new materials. The translator does not copy the statue; she recasts it, and asks whether the new bronze still does what the marble did.`;
const VH10 = `The deeds are clean, the lawyer was emphatic;
no cloud upon the title, all is sound.
Yet some nights, in the settling of the attic,
I hear the previous owner of the ground,

not ghost exactly, more a kind of pressure,
the way a debt you did not make can press,
and wonder if a man may hold in pleasure
a thing he came to honestly, no less

for having come to it across the ruin
of someone forced to sign and walk away.
The house is mine. That is not the undoing.
The undoing is how little I will pay.`;
const VH11 = `For thirty years Agnes had carried the memory of how the Pooles took her in during the bad winter, fed her at their own table, and asked nothing of it, and she had repaid them in a thousand small kindnesses, watching the house, minding the dog, sitting with the old man at the end. It was only when she came to sort her sister's letters that she found, in her own girlish hand, the account of that winter: how the Pooles had charged her for the room, and how cold the table had been, and how glad she was to leave. She sat with the letter a long time. The kindness she had spent thirty years repaying had not occurred. And yet the dog had been minded, the old man comforted, the house kept. She found she did not want the years back.`;
const VH12 = `When two experts of equal standing disagree, the layman is often advised to suspend judgement, and the advice sounds humble. But suspension is itself a verdict, the verdict that the two positions are equally supported, and the layman is no better placed to reach that verdict than to choose between the experts directly. He cannot weigh the arguments, by hypothesis, or he would not be a layman; so when he declares the dispute a tie he is not refraining from judgement but smuggling one in under a modest name. The honest position is harder: to admit that he must defer, and then to face the genuinely difficult question of which marks of trustworthiness, a track record, the absence of a stake, the assent of others competent to judge, a layman can recognise without himself becoming an expert.`;
const VH13 = `There is a bird I cannot name, and so
it sings the better, being only sound
and not the box I would have filed it under;
the field guide in my pocket, page on page,
is where the living go to be embalmed.
I close it. Now the morning is a wonder
I have no word for, which is why it stays
a wonder, and does not become a page.`;
const VH14 = `We are most sure we could have done otherwise in just those cases where, on reflection, we would not have wanted to. Asked whether I might have betrayed my friend, I feel the full openness of the alternative and affirm my freedom; yet had I been the sort of man who could betray him there, I would not have been the friend I am, and the deed would not have tempted me at all. The freedom I prize, then, is not a freedom to act against my character but a freedom that flows from it, and the cases that seem to display an unconditioned will turn out, looked at closely, to be the cases in which my will is most thoroughly conditioned by who I am. What feels like a door standing open is more often the shape of a wall I have become.`;
const VH15 = `Mr Avery told the boy, kindly, that talent like his was a fragile thing, easily spoiled by praise, and that he would do him the service the world would not, of keeping his expectations modest. He marked the boy a grade below what the work deserved, explaining that genius must learn to survive injustice. When the boy won the regional prize despite him, Mr Avery spoke movingly at assembly of the dangers of early success, and watched the boy's face for the shadow his words were designed to cast. He told himself, and almost believed, that he was protecting the child from the disappointments he himself had met at that age, in a corridor of this same school, when a door he had counted on had failed to open.`;
const VH16 = `A monument does not record the past; it makes a proposal about it, and the proposal is most persuasive when it looks least like one. The bronze general on his horse does not argue that the war was worth its dead, he simply stands, in the calm of settled fact, where argument has the air of bad manners. This is why quarrels over statues are not quarrels about history but about which proposals shall enjoy the privilege of seeming natural. To leave a monument standing is not neutral, for the standing is itself the claim; and to remove one is not to erase the past but to withdraw a particular endorsement the present had been renewing, almost without noticing, every day it let the figure stand.`;
const VH17 = `This is the only picture of you laughing,
and it has made your laughter into this:
a single instant, lifted, doing duty
for all the times I failed to lift a lens.

I loved the sound, and have instead the silence
of a mouth held open on a joke now lost;
the camera kept the proof and dropped the meaning,
the way a coin outlasts the thing it cost.`;
const VH18 = `The golden age is always the one just before the speaker's own disappointments began. Each generation remembers a time when neighbours knew one another, work was honest, and children were safe, and locates it, with suspicious regularity, in the years of its own childhood, which is to say in the only period it experienced without responsibility. What is recalled is not a better world but a smaller one, seen from below, in which the troubles that later pressed upon us had not yet been handed over to our keeping. To compare that remembered ease with our present burdens and conclude that the world has declined is to mistake the lightening of a child's load for the strengthening of the times, and to grieve, under the name of a lost golden age, for nothing more than the loss of being young.`;

const TST1 = "To explain an action is to show how it came about; to excuse it is to lessen the agent's responsibility for it. The two are constantly confused, and the confusion runs in both directions. Those who fear that understanding a cruelty will end by pardoning it refuse to look for its causes, as though ignorance were a form of moral vigilance. Their opponents, having found the causes, conclude that blame is therefore misplaced, as though to be explicable were the same as to be involuntary. Both have made the identical mistake from opposite sides: they assume that a complete causal account of a deed must compete with holding its author to account. But a full explanation of why a man lied no more dissolves his responsibility than a full explanation of why a bridge fell absolves the engineer who skimped on the steel. We may understand everything and forgive nothing; the choice to forgive, when it comes, is a further act, not a conclusion forced upon us by the explanation.";
const TST2 = "When their father died, it was Margaret who made the arrangements, chose the hymns, and stood dry-eyed at the front while her brother wept handsomely into a borrowed handkerchief and was much consoled by the neighbours. Afterwards they said what a comfort the son had been, and how strange the daughter, so cold, so capable. Only the undertaker, a man practised in reading the bereaved, noticed that she had asked for the coffin to be turned a few degrees so that it faced the window, and the garden their father had loved, and that she checked, twice, that it had been done. He said nothing. He had learned that the ones who arrange the flowers are not always the ones who feel the least, and that grief, denied its usual exits, will leave by the narrowest of doors.";
const TST3 = `They clapped him to the door and down the stair,
the speech still warm, the verdict full and kind;
he carried out their praise like borrowed plate,
afraid to look too closely at the shine.

For he had said the thing they came to hear,
and they had paid him in the coin of cheer,
and somewhere in the keeping of the sound
he understood the bargain, and the year

ahead of him, in which he would repeat
the sentence that had pleased them, word for word,
until the day the clapping was the speech,
and none, not least himself, still heard.`;
const TST4 = "A common complaint holds that to tolerate a practice is, in effect, to endorse it, and that a state which permits what it could forbid has already taken sides. The complaint mistakes the nature of toleration, which is not indifference but restraint: one tolerates only what one would, if asked, condemn, for there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. To permit a thing one dislikes is therefore not a covert endorsement but its precise opposite, a refusal to let one's disapproval do the work of a prohibition. The genuine danger lies elsewhere. A society may grow so used to permitting what it dislikes that it forgets it dislikes it at all, and toleration, which began as disapproval held in check, decays by degrees into the very indifference it was once mistaken for.";

const TST5 = `To have a right to do something is not to be right in doing it. The confusion of the two is among the most persistent in public argument. A man may have every right to spend his last shilling on drink, to publish a book of malicious gossip, or to refuse the friend who needs him; and in each case we may say, without contradiction, that he ought not to have done so. A right marks out a sphere within which a choice is the agent's own to make, protected from interference; it does not certify that the choice, once made, is wise or good. To defend a person's right to act is therefore not to praise the act, and the careless slide from the first to the second has done much to coarsen the way we speak of liberty.

The slide runs in both directions. Those who dislike an act are tempted to deny that anyone could have a right to it, as though the wrongness of a deed were enough to strip away its protection; and those who wish to defend an act find it easier to call it harmless than to make the harder argument that, harmful or not, it lies within the agent's protected sphere. Both evade the same difficulty. The whole point of a right is that it binds us even where we judge its exercise to be mistaken, for a liberty that extended only to the choices of which others approved would be no liberty at all, but merely approval wearing its costume.`;
const TST6 = `Everyone in the parish knew of Henshaw's generosity, because Henshaw took care that they should. The new roof on the almshouse bore a small brass plate with his name; the scholarship for poor scholars was the Henshaw Scholarship; and when he gave, which was often, he gave at the moment when giving would be seen. The vicar, who depended on him, called him a pillar; the schoolmaster, who did not, called him a man who had discovered that virtue, advertised, pays a better rate of interest than virtue concealed.

And yet there was this to be said. The plate on the almshouse was small, smaller than he could have afforded; the scholarship was real, and the scholars it raised owed nothing in return; and the schoolmaster, pressing his case, could never quite explain why a man who gave only for the look of the thing should give quite so much, or to causes so unlikely to repay him. Self-interest is an economical hypothesis, but it is not always the most economical; sometimes it must strain harder to explain a deed than mere kindness would.`;
const TST7 = `When a fire destroys a warehouse, the report names a cause: a frayed wire, perhaps, or a dropped cigarette. Yet the wire could have sparked for years in a damp cellar and started nothing; the fire needed oxygen, dry timber, the absence of a sprinkler, a hundred standing conditions no report will mention. To call the spark the cause and the oxygen a mere condition is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice about where, among the countless things without which it would not have happened, our interest and our blame should fall.

The choice is rarely innocent. We name as the cause the condition we think someone should have altered, so that the search for causes is already, half-secretly, a search for the responsible. The factory owner calls it the careless worker; the union calls it the missing sprinkler; each has found, with perfect sincerity, the real cause, and each has in truth selected, from a single web of necessity, the strand that points where they were already looking.`;
const TST8 = "They called the doctor a plain man, and he did not contradict them, though he knew the word was doing more work than they supposed. To his patients it meant unfrightening, a man who would not dress a verdict in Latin; to his colleagues it meant limited, a man who had not kept up; to his wife, who had watched him sit all night with the dying for no fee, it meant something nearer to the old sense of the word, the sense in which a plain is open country with nothing to hide behind. He let each of them keep their meaning. He had found that a word everyone thought they understood was the safest possible disguise.";
const TST9 = `They asked me to keep the garden as it was
the year she planted it, and so each spring
I cut the climbing rose to the same height,
and pull the seedlings she would not have let
take root, and call it faithfulness. The bed
obeys a hand that is no longer here;
I am the means by which her absence gardens.

And sometimes, kneeling, I will let one weed
grow on a week beyond its sentence, just
to see the plot do something she would not have chosen,
and feel, in that small mutiny of green,
how heavy is the keeping of a shape
against the patient argument of seed,
and whether to preserve a thing is, slowly,
to stand between it and the life it wants.`;
const TST10 = `The word natural has become a term of praise, and unnatural an accusation, as though the question of whether a thing occurs without our intervention settled the question of whether it is good. But nature, considered honestly, is no reliable guide to value. Disease is natural; the antibiotic is not. Cruelty between animals is natural; the hospital is a standing rebuke to it. If we mean by natural whatever happens of itself, then much of what is natural is dreadful, and much of our moral effort consists precisely in resisting it.

The defender of nature may retreat to a narrower claim: not that the natural is good, but that we should be cautious in overriding arrangements we did not design and do not fully understand. This is wiser, but it is a different argument, resting on our ignorance rather than on nature's authority, and it cuts both ways: the same humility that warns against tampering with an ecosystem warns against assuming that what is customary is therefore sound. Caution is not reverence, and the prudent man and the worshipper of nature, though they may walk together for a while, are not going to the same place.`;
const TST11 = "Aunt Vera gave advice the way other people give gifts, generously and without being asked, and she could not understand why it was so seldom welcome. She had, she would say, only ever told people the truth about themselves, as if the truth were a parcel one was obliged to accept on delivery. It did not occur to her that the gift might be less for the receiver than for the giver, that to be the one who sees clearly and says so is a pleasure in itself, and that the relish with which she diagnosed the failings of her nieces was not quite the same thing as a wish to cure them.";
const TST12 = "An instructor notices that when he praises a cadet for an excellent landing, the next landing is usually worse, while when he berates one for a poor landing, the next is usually better. He concludes that criticism works and praise spoils, and he is far from alone. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is, by definition, partly luck, and the next attempt will tend to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level; an unusually bad one, likewise, will tend to be followed by something nearer the average. The improvement and the decline are not effects of his feedback but artefacts of measuring a fluctuating skill at its extremes.";
const TST13 = `He left me, in the end, no house, no land,
no watch to wind, no letters tied with string,
but a particular way of holding back
the very word that might have changed a thing.

I have it still. I feel it in my mouth
at the precise moment it would cost me most
to speak, and do not speak, and call it tact,
and lay a wreath each year upon his ghost,

and tend, without quite meaning to, the one
estate he could be certain to bequeath:
the silence that he taught me, passed along
intact, to those who stand and grieve beneath.`;
const TST14 = "We are often urged to be consistent, as though consistency were itself a virtue. But consistency is only the agreement of our beliefs with one another, not their agreement with the truth, and a man may be perfectly consistent and perfectly wrong. The miser is consistent; the fanatic is consistent; it is the open mind, revising itself as the evidence shifts, that must accept the charge of inconsistency as the price of being responsive to the world. To prize consistency above correction is to prefer the tidiness of one's opinions to their truth.";
const TST15 = "The new manager believed in what he called frankness, and he practised it chiefly upon those who could not answer back. With his own superiors he was a model of nuance, discovering on every contested question a complexity that required further thought; it was only downward that the truth became simple enough to state plainly. His staff came to know the weather of his honesty, which blew, like most weather, from the regions of low pressure toward the high, and never the other way.";
const TST16 = `For thirty years he knew the part by heart,
the pauses, the one gesture at the close,
and waited in the wings, in case. The star
grew old but did not falter, and the rows

applauded, year on year, a face he could
have worn more truly. When at last he died,
they found the margins of his only script
unmarked, as though there had been nothing to decide;

and could not tell, who came to clear the room,
if this was discipline, or a long despair,
or whether, standing nightly in the dark,
he had become the role by playing air.`;
const TST17 = "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are no longer in crisis a year later, and asks us to admire the result. The figure may be true and still tell us almost nothing, for we are not told how many families in the same circumstances, given no help at all, would have recovered within the year by the ordinary action of time and their own efforts. Without that comparison the ninety per cent is a number in search of a meaning: impressive, unanchored, and exactly the kind of figure that is easiest to raise money with and hardest to learn anything from.";
const TST18 = "Few words are asked to carry as much, on as little, as deserve. The successful say they deserve their rewards, meaning that they worked for them; their critics say they do not, meaning that the work was made possible by advantages they did not earn. Both are right about what they assert and wrong about what they deny, for the word slides between two senses, the one rewarding effort and the other auditing its conditions, and a quarrel in which each party uses the same word for a different thing is not a disagreement so much as a collision.";
const TST19 = "When the river rose, the village was praised in the newspapers for its spirit: how neighbours had carried neighbours, how the baker had given away his stock. What the newspapers did not say, because no one had told them and no one quite wished to, was that the same flood had washed out a year of small unkindnesses, the disputed fence, the unreturned ladder, the wedding slight, and that the spirit so admired was partly the relief of people glad of a disaster large enough to make their meannesses look small. They were not lying when they embraced. But they were also burying something, under water that would, in time, go down.";
const TST20 = `He kept the butterflies behind the glass,
each pinned at the exact angle of its flight,
and said he loved them. Maybe so. The room
was very still, and very full of light,

and nothing in it moved, or would again,
or fed, or failed, or frightened off, or flew.
He had the colours. What he could not keep,
and called unimportant, was the only true

and fugitive thing about them: that they go.
To hold a wing is not to hold the flight.
He owned a hundred specimens of blue
and not one living instance of the blue.`;

const GAMSAT_S1_QUESTIONS = [
  { id: "gs1-prose-001", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-sp1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage most fully supports which account of why Halloran 'never once spoke of closing'?", format: "single_best", options: ["admitting it would mean accepting that he, and the shop, had outlived any use the world had for them", "he still half-believed the shop might revive, so naming closure felt premature", "admitting it would mean confessing a personal failure he could not bring himself to own", "to name closure aloud would be to abandon a fight he meant to keep up"], answer: 0, explanation: "All four give a motive for the silence, so none is eliminable by topic. The text ties it to one admission, that he and the shop belonged to a world with no use for them, which is the obsolescence reading; the personal-failure version is its near-twin but mischaracterises it, since the passage frames the loss as the world having no use for him, not a failure he committed. The half-believed and abandon-a-fight options share a different reading, that he was hopeful or defiant, yet his polishing only seems to hold back the tide, which marks it futile rather than hopeful.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-002", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sp1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Polishing the counter harder and arriving earlier are presented as gestures that are...", format: "single_best", options: ["practical measures that modestly improved his position against the supermarket", "comforting habits he kept up only after privately accepting that the end had come", "small rituals that could not affect the outcome but let him put off facing it", "a disciplined effort to win back the customers he had been losing"], answer: 2, explanation: "Each option treats the gestures as purposeful, so topic is no guide. As though punctuality alone might hold back the tide marks them futile yet face-saving, the put-off-facing-it reading; the privately-accepted twin sits in the same family but contradicts the passage, whose whole point is that he has not accepted the end. The improved-position and win-back options share the opposite reading, that the efforts worked, which the image's futility denies.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-003", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-sp1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's attitude toward Halloran is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["sympathetic, admiring the dignity of his refusal to give in", "sympathetic, alert to the pathos of his self-deception but not mocking it", "gently ironic at the futility of his daily rituals", "detached, recording his decline without evident feeling"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options are warm and two cool, so the reader weighs shades rather than topic. The narrator treats his self-deception with feeling but not ridicule, the pathos-without-mockery reading; the admiring twin overstates, since the text pities rather than celebrates his refusal. The ironic and detached options share the cool reading, but the closing line, that he too may belong to a world with no use for him, carries plain sympathy, not irony or distance.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-004", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sp1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, the phrase 'hold back the tide' works chiefly to...", format: "single_best", options: ["the mounting effort he must make merely to keep the shop open", "the competition from the new supermarket in particular", "his own conviction that diligence could still turn things around", "the broad change that is quietly making his shop, and his world, obsolete"], answer: 3, explanation: "The tide is what he tries to hold back, so all four are candidates for what it figures. It is the larger movement that has no use for the shop, the broad-change reading; the supermarket twin is the same family but too narrow, since the passage widens it to a whole world. The effort and conviction options misplace the tide onto his own action rather than the force opposing him.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-005", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sp1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is best read as...", format: "single_best", options: ["the displacement of small traders by larger competitors", "one man's quiet grief at having outlived the world he belonged to", "one man's refusal to admit that his world has passed him by", "the human cost that economic change imposes on a community"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options read the passage as one man's inner state and two as a social theme, so the reader must fix the level first. It is an interior refusal to admit obsolescence, the denial reading; the grief twin is close but wrong, since he will not acknowledge the loss enough to grieve it. The displacement and human-cost options generalise to society, which the passage, fixed on this one man's silence, never does.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-006", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sp2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Eleanor's telling herself she was 'simply busy' is best understood as...", format: "single_best", options: ["an accurate account: the garden and accounts genuinely did come first", "an excuse she half-believes, masking a fear she will not look at directly", "a conscious pretext she uses to put others off the delay", "a sign the letter mattered too little to open at once"], answer: 1, explanation: "All four interpret the busyness, so none is off-topic. She tells herself she is busy while walking faster past the envelope, which marks it as self-deception, the half-believed-excuse reading; the conscious-pretext twin is wrong because the deception is aimed inward (told herself), not at others. The genuinely-came-first and mattered-too-little options share the opposite reading, that the busyness was real, which her quickening step contradicts.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-007", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sp2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing reflection turns chiefly on the idea that...", format: "single_best", options: ["feared news usually turns out gentler than we suppose", "the relief of good news outweighs the cost of having waited", "facing a fear is always lighter than we expect it to be", "the dread we sustain in imagination can weigh more than the thing once it is met"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options are about the news or outcome and two about the weight of dread, so the reader picks the right axis first. The claim is that imagined dread outweighs the faced reality, the weight-of-dread reading; the always-lighter twin overstates it into a law, where the passage offers a single observation. The gentler-news and relief-outweighs options shift to how news turns out, which is not the point about dread.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-008", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sp2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The simile of hurrying 'past a window one does not wish to look through' most precisely conveys that Eleanor's avoidance was...", format: "single_best", options: ["an almost involuntary quickening away from what she dreads to see", "a deliberate decision to postpone reading the letter for now", "a discomfort with the hallway she would rather not linger in", "an impatience to press on with her many tasks"], answer: 0, explanation: "The first two read the act as avoidance of the letter, the last two as being about the place or her busyness. It is an instinctive flinch, the involuntary-quickening reading; the deliberate-decision twin is wrong, since she still tells herself she is merely busy rather than choosing to avoid. The hallway and tasks options relocate the aversion onto the room or her schedule, not the feared news.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-009", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-sp2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's closing mood is most precisely described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["quiet joy, the worry now wholly behind her", "calm satisfaction at having managed a hard moment well", "relief, shaded by a rueful sense that her dread had been out of proportion", "relief, mixed mainly with surprise that the news proved so kind"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options are simple positives and two are relief joined to a reflection, so the fine call is which reflection. Being surprised that dread weighs less than imagined points to rue at her own disproportion, the out-of-proportion reading; the surprise-at-kindness twin is its near-double but shallower, naming the news rather than her dread. The joy and satisfaction options drop the reflective edge the close clearly carries.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-010", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sp3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is best understood as an account of...", format: "single_best", options: ["the gradual loss of his attachment to the village he left", "the estrangement from family that distance tends to bring", "the quiet acquiring of a second self, until he cannot tell which life is real", "the slow replacing of his old self by the person the city made him"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options read the change as losing home and two as a change in the self, so the reader fixes the theme first. It is a second self gained beside the first, the cannot-tell-which-is-real reading; the replacement twin is wrong, since the passage gives him two lives at once, not the old one erased. The attachment and estrangement options are denied outright, the silence is not because he forgot or withdrew from home.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-011", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sp3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The detail that the letters stopped 'not because he had forgotten his village' implies that the cause of the silence was...", format: "single_best", options: ["his attachment to the village had quietly faded", "he had simply run out of news worth sending", "he had at last settled comfortably into the city", "a change in him, his ceasing to find the double life strange"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options locate the cause outside him (fading ties, no news) and two inside him, so the fine call is which inner change. The text says he no longer found it strange to have two lives, the ceased-to-find-it-strange reading; the settled-in twin is close but wrong, since he ends unable to say which life is the disguise, hardly the mark of comfortable settling. The faded-attachment and no-news options are the externals the passage explicitly sets aside.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-012", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-sp3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of 'a coin sewn into a coat' captures Tomas's early assumption that one's home self is...", format: "single_best", options: ["carried within, intact and unaltered by wherever one goes", "a hidden reserve one can always draw upon", "a secret best kept from new acquaintances", "a valuable thing that others may try to take"], answer: 0, explanation: "The first two keep the coin as something carried inside, the last two read it as a secret or a target for theft. It figures identity travelling intact, the unaltered-within reading; the reserve twin is close but wrong, since the point is unbroken continuity, not a resource to be spent. The secret and theft options import concealment and danger the passage never raises.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-013", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-sp3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The change in Tomas from the first year to the third is best described as a move from...", format: "single_best", options: ["homesickness for the village to feeling fully at home in the city", "holding his village self to be the real one to being unable to say which self is real", "a single self to two, one of which he still privately knows to be the disguise", "fascination with the city to a quiet disenchantment with it"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options track his certainty about which self is real and two track his mood, so the reader picks the axis first. He moves from treating home as the real self to being unable to rank them, the cannot-say-which reading; the still-knows-the-disguise twin is wrong, since the passage says he can no longer tell. The homesickness and disenchantment options are about comfort or mood, not the identity question at the centre.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-014", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sp3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SP3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage implies that the original warning that the city 'would change him' was...", format: "single_best", options: ["proved mistaken, since he kept his village self after all", "rendered beside the point, the change owing more to time than to the city", "confirmed in just the sense the warner is likely to have meant", "borne out, but as a quiet inward doubling rather than the coarsening such warnings usually imply"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options say the warning did not really hold and two say it did, so the fine call is in what sense. It was borne out, but inwardly and subtly, the quiet-doubling reading; the just-as-intended twin is wrong, since such warnings usually mean a plainer coarsening, not this. The mistaken and beside-the-point options deny the change the passage clearly records, crediting his constancy or time instead of the city he was warned about.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-001", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-po1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO1, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem is best read as a meditation on...", format: "single_best", options: ["the natural cycle of blossom and decay in an old orchard", "something planted in hope and then left unclaimed, yet still offering its gift", "the regret of those who let a promising thing go to waste", "the beauty of an orchard left to grow wild"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options centre the neglected, still-giving orchard and two read it literally as nature. The subject is a thing planted in hope, left unclaimed, yet giving still, the ongoing-gift reading; the regret twin shifts the centre to the planters' feelings, where the poem keeps it on the orchard's ungrudging offering. The cycle and wild-beauty options take the orchard literally, missing the human meaning.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-002", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-po1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO1, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The tone of the poem is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["wistful, touched with quiet self-reproach", "elegiac, mourning the orchard as good as dead", "lightly playful about a familiar scene", "serenely content with the orchard's wild beauty"], answer: 0, explanation: "Two options are sad-toned and two light, so the call is a shade. The we meant to but left it is wistful with gentle self-reproach; the elegiac twin overstates into mourning a death, yet the orchard tries again each spring, alive. The playful and content options miss the regret entirely.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-003", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-po1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO1, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The phrase 'as if forgetting were a kind of grace' presents the orchard's yearly blossoming as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a reproach to the owners who failed to harvest", "a sign that the orchard is nearing its end", "a mindless persistence, blossoming only out of habit", "an ungrudging generosity, giving again as if the neglect were forgiven"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options read the renewed blossom as ongoing giving and two as rebuke or decline. Forgetting as grace makes it an ungrudging gift, offered again as if the neglect were forgiven; the mindless-habit twin shares the persistence but drains the tenderness the word grace supplies. The reproach option transfers the speaker's regret onto the orchard, and the end option misreads a tree that keeps trying.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-004", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-po1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO1, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The line 'we meant to pick the fruit ourselves' chiefly conveys...", format: "single_best", options: ["a deliberate choice to leave the fruit for the birds", "a memory of harvests they once enjoyed together", "an intention formed but never carried through, the fruit left to fall", "a promise to others that the speakers failed to keep"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options read the line as an unfulfilled intention and two as a choice or a memory. Meant to, but left it to fall, is an intention never carried out, the neglect reading; the promise-to-others twin shares the failure but mistakes its object, since they meant to pick the fruit for themselves. The leave-for-birds option makes neglect into a kindly choice, and the memory option invents past harvests the poem does not give.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-005", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-po2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem is chiefly a portrait of...", format: "single_best", options: ["a devotion that persists after the purpose it served has gone", "the obsolescence of lighthouses in a modern age", "a man's loyalty to a duty he is still required to perform", "the loneliness of a man cut off at the coast"], answer: 0, explanation: "Two options concern the nature of his devotion and two point elsewhere, to the era or his solitude. It is devotion outliving its purpose, freely kept though the ships have gone, the purposeless-devotion reading; the still-required twin calls it obligation, but nothing now requires it. The obsolescence and loneliness options shift to the technology or his isolation, not the faithfulness the poem dwells on.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-006", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-po2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "That the keeper 'asks of no one why, or how' most strongly implies that his faithfulness...", format: "single_best", options: ["springs from a hope that the ships will one day return", "needs no reason beyond itself to continue", "has become an automatic routine he no longer questions", "is held up by a fear of being blamed if the lamp should go dark"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options read his not-asking as self-sufficient principle and two as hope or fear. Asking of no one why or how marks a faithfulness that needs no external reason, sustained by duty, pride, a vow; the automatic-routine twin shares the not-asking but empties it of the principle the poem names. The hope and fear options supply motives the steady keeper never shows.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-007", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-po2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The speaker's attitude toward the keeper is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["gently mocking the pointlessness of his vigil", "pitying him as a forgotten relic", "reverent, holding his vigil up as a noble example", "quietly admiring, without pretending the task is still needed"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options are warm toward the keeper and two cool, so the call is a shade. It is quiet admiration that does not pretend the bay needs him, the clear-eyed-respect reading; the reverent twin overstates into holding him up as a noble exemplar, where call it duty, call it pride stays wry. The mocking and pitying options miss the respect the poem plainly carries.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-008", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-po2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The lamp lit for an 'empty bay' serves chiefly as an image of...", format: "single_best", options: ["the waste of tending a lighthouse no ship needs", "a hope that the light will yet draw the ships back", "faithfulness kept up though there is no longer anyone to receive it", "the isolation that has hollowed out the keeper's life"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options read the lamp as faithful keeping and two as waste or loneliness. A light lit for an empty bay figures devotion with no one left to receive it, the no-audience reading; the hope-of-return twin shares the focus on the lamp's purpose but supplies a hope the poem withholds. The waste option takes a cynical view the poem rejects, and the isolation option shifts to his solitude rather than his faithfulness.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-009", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-po3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem's central realisation is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["what seemed the water's own voice was in fact shaped by the silent stone", "the river simply grew quieter as autumn came on", "the water and the stone were equal partners in the sound he heard", "the stone proved stronger than the water in the end"], answer: 0, explanation: "Two options read the sound as shaped by the stone and two read it as season or strength, so the reader fixes the relation first. Autumn shows it was the stone that shaped what he heard, the stone-shaped reading; the equal-partners twin shares the water-and-stone frame but the poem makes the water only borrow what the stone gives, not share it equally. The quieter-in-autumn option is seasonal literalism, and the stronger-stone option turns shaping into a contest of strength.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-010", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-po3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The 'argument' between river and stone works as a figure for...", format: "single_best", options: ["the gradual wearing-away and ruin of a landscape", "a quiet, enduring force silently governing a loud and showy one", "two opposed forces locked in a contest that neither can win", "a pleasant natural sound the speaker enjoys on a walk"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options read the figure as a relation between forces and two as ruin or mere sound. The still stone shapes the noisy water, so a quiet enduring force governs a loud showy one, the governed reading; the stalemate twin keeps the two-forces frame but the poem has one shaping the other, not a deadlock. The wearing-away option overreads wore away into landscape ruin, and the pleasant-sound option takes the argument literally.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-011", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-po3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "If 'stubborn' in 'the stubborn sentence it appeared to say' were replaced, which word would best preserve the sense?", format: "single_best", options: ["truculent", "perennial", "adamantine", "obdurate"], answer: 3, explanation: "Stubborn here means hardened and unyielding, the stone's quality lent to the sound, which is obdurate, literally hardened. Adamantine is the close miss, naming a physical hardness like diamond rather than the unyielding persistence of an assertion. Truculent means aggressively defiant, a hostility the line does not carry. Perennial means recurring year after year, a matter of time, not unyieldingness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-012", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-po3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The speaker's attitude in the closing lines is one of...", format: "single_best", options: ["quiet frustration at having been so long deceived", "private pride at having seen through the illusion", "calm acceptance of a correction quietly received", "gentle wonder at a mystery he cannot fully explain"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options are calm and two are sharp, so the reader weighs the shade. Ending on the quiet of the stone, he accepts the correction serenely, the calm-acceptance reading; the wonder twin keeps the calm but the poem resolves the puzzle, the stone shaped it, rather than leaving an unexplained mystery. The frustration and pride options supply a grievance or self-congratulation the close does not carry.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-001", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central claim is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["screens are the main driver of the rise in teenage anxiety", "the reported rise in teenage anxiety has been exaggerated", "a correlation between screens and anxiety does not, by itself, establish that screens are the cause", "academic pressure, not screens, is the true cause of the anxiety"], answer: 2, explanation: "The author resists reading the correlation as proof of cause while naming rival factors, endorsing none. The main-driver option is the view warned against. The exaggerated option is never claimed, the rise is granted. The academic-pressure option over-commits to one rival the author merely lists.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-002", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of mistaking 'a crowded room for an empty one' conveys that...", format: "single_best", options: ["other possible causes are present but go unnoticed once attention fixes on screens", "the data sample is too small to support any conclusion", "the rise in anxiety is not real", "screens are plainly the only factor at work"], answer: 0, explanation: "The room is crowded with rival causes, so fixing on screens treats a full room as empty. The sample option misreads the figure as a point about size. The not-real option contradicts the granted rise. The only-factor option is the very error the image exposes.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-003", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author would be most likely to agree that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the screen-time limits should be repealed", "smartphones have no effect on teenage wellbeing", "teenagers are not in fact more anxious than before", "a single cause should not be inferred from a correlation among several plausible factors"], answer: 3, explanation: "The passage's whole counsel is caution about inferring one cause from correlation. The repeal option takes a policy stand the author avoids. The no-effect option rules screens out, which the author does not. The not-anxious option denies the rise the author grants.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-004", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'the one we happened to be looking for' implies that screens may have been singled out because...", format: "single_best", options: ["the data clearly proved screens to be the cause", "observers were already disposed to find screens at fault", "screens are the most important of the possible causes", "the other factors had each been ruled out by evidence"], answer: 1, explanation: "Happened to be looking for points to a prior disposition shaping which cause gets named. The proved option is the reverse. The most-important option asserts the ranking the passage doubts. The ruled-out option wrongly says the rivals were eliminated.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-005", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, addedInfo: "A study published after this passage now follows ten thousand teenagers for five years. It reports that those who cut their daily screen time by half showed no measurable change in anxiety, while a separate group whose schools reduced academic workload did show a modest decline.", stem: "How does this additional finding bear on the argument in the passage?", format: "single_best", options: ["It supports the author's caution, since screens may not be the operative cause while a rival factor shows an effect", "It proves that screens cannot affect anxiety at all", "It contradicts the passage by confirming that screens cause anxiety", "It can be set aside because it was published after the passage was written"], answer: 0, explanation: "The passage warned against treating screens as the proven cause. A finding that halving screen time changed anxiety not at all, while cutting workload did, supports that caution and points to a rival factor rather than overturning the argument.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-006", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "A defender of the original screen-time limits could most reasonably reply that...", format: "single_best", options: ["academic workload cannot influence anxiety", "the new study must be fraudulent", "halving screen time, or a five-year window, may be too little to reveal a real but small or slow effect", "a correlation always proves causation after all"], answer: 2, explanation: "The strongest reply keeps the limits defensible without denying the data: a modest or slow effect might not surface within five years or from a half reduction. The other options deny the evidence or contradict the passage's own logic.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-014", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["societies should treat their prisoners more comfortably", "judging a society by how it treats its prisoners is a less stable test than it appears", "every era treats its prisoners cruelly by later standards", "a society should never condemn anyone at all"], answer: 1, explanation: "The maxim is unstable because the standard moves with the values of the judge, so the author proposes a different measure. The comfort option is not a prescription he makes. The every-era option overgeneralises. The never-condemn option is extreme, since he urges care before condemning, not no condemning.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-015", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's main objection to the popular principle is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["prisoners can never be treated fairly in practice", "comfort is too difficult to measure reliably", "societies in fact rarely condemn anyone", "what counts as humane treatment shifts with the values of the judging era"], answer: 3, explanation: "The instability of the standard, humane to one era, cruel or indulgent to another, is the objection. The fairly option is not raised. The measure option misreads the trouble as measurement rather than a moving standard. The rarely-condemn option is false.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-007", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "As a more revealing measure of a society, the author proposes...", format: "single_best", options: ["the care it takes before condemning anyone at all", "how comfortable it makes its prisons", "how swiftly it punishes the guilty", "how few people it imprisons"], answer: 0, explanation: "The close offers the care taken before condemning as the better measure. The comfort option is the measure he sets aside. The swiftly option is never proposed. The how-few option sounds related but is not his measure, which concerns care before condemning, not the raw number.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-008", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-sb2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's stance toward the popular maxim is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["enthusiastic endorsement", "outright contempt", "qualified scepticism, finding it appealing yet flawed", "complete indifference"], answer: 2, explanation: "He calls the maxim appealing but shows it conceals a difficulty, which is qualified scepticism. The endorsement option ignores the qualification. The contempt option is too harsh for something he finds appealing. The indifference option is belied by his close engagement.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-009", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The central flaw the author identifies is that the policy's advocates...", format: "single_best", options: ["never measure the policy's outcomes at all", "blame the public whenever the policy fails", "refuse to fund the policy adequately", "have arranged matters so that no outcome could ever count against the policy"], answer: 3, explanation: "Crediting design for success and execution for failure makes the policy unfalsifiable. The never-measure option is the near-miss, but advocates do attend to outcomes, they just reinterpret each one. The blame-public option misreads execution as the public. The funding option is never raised.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-010", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Calling the claimed success 'an article of faith' charges that it is...", format: "single_best", options: ["believed regardless of what the evidence shows", "backed by unusually strong evidence", "a religious doctrine in the literal sense", "a view held only tentatively"], answer: 0, explanation: "An article of faith here is belief independent of evidence, the charge against an unfalsifiable success. The strong-evidence option is the reverse. The religious option literalises the figure. The tentative option contradicts the firmness of faith.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-011", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "A genuine test of the policy, the author says, would require its advocates to...", format: "single_best", options: ["spend more money before judging it", "state in advance what result would show them to be wrong", "consult the public before acting", "wait longer before drawing conclusions"], answer: 1, explanation: "The test is to specify beforehand what outcome would prove them wrong. The money, consult and wait options each name something the passage never makes the criterion of a real test.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-012", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is best summarised as an argument that...", format: "single_best", options: ["all government policy should be abandoned", "the policy in question has in fact succeeded", "a claim that no possible outcome could disprove tells us nothing", "experts should be trusted over the public"], answer: 2, explanation: "The passage turns on falsifiability, treating an undisprovable claim as faith, not evidence. The abandon-all option overreaches. The succeeded option is the reverse. The experts option is unrelated.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },



  { id: "gs1-graphic-007", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-gr3", stimulus: { kind: "table", content: GR3, attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "The footnote that the surveys were conducted 'outside the proposed northern on-ramp' most undermines confidence in...", format: "single_best", options: ["the South's 59% opposition", "the total number of people surveyed", "the North's 62% support, by oversampling those likely to benefit", "the honesty of the survey's designers"], answer: 2, explanation: "Sampling at the on-ramp gathers those who would gain from the bridge, inflating northern Yes. The South option is untouched, since the footnote concerns the northern site. The total option is not what bias affects. The honesty option overreaches, this is a methodological bias, not proven dishonesty.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-008", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-gr3", stimulus: { kind: "table", content: GR3, attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "Taking the percentages and the sample sizes together, the data most strongly indicate that...", format: "single_best", options: ["across both regions, more respondents opposed the bridge than supported it", "support and opposition are evenly balanced overall", "the two regions surveyed roughly equal numbers", "overall support clearly outweighs opposition"], answer: 0, explanation: "The large southern sample of 1,180 at 59% opposed outweighs the small northern Yes, so more opposed overall. The balanced option ignores that gap. The equal-numbers option overlooks 420 against 1,180. The support option is the reverse of the totals.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-009", genre: "graphic", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-gr3", stimulus: { kind: "table", content: GR3, attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "The table works best as a caution that...", format: "single_best", options: ["surveys are inherently untrustworthy", "the North is a more reliable region than the South", "bridges are unpopular in most places", "headline percentages can mislead unless sample size and method are weighed"], answer: 3, explanation: "The differing samples and the location footnote show why raw percentages mislead without method and scale. The untrustworthy option is too sweeping. The North option reverses things, since the northern figure is the suspect one. The unpopular option overgeneralises from one survey.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-011", genre: "graphic", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-grc1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: GRC1, alt: "A well-dressed figure stands near the top of a ladder labelled OPPORTUNITY and saws off the rung just beneath his feet while declaring that anyone can climb up. The rungs below are already broken, and a worker at the bottom reaches up toward the ladder.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "The cartoon's central point is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["ladders are a poor symbol for social mobility", "those who have already risen praise opportunity while removing the means for others to follow", "the worker at the bottom is simply not trying hard enough", "rising requires no help from anyone"], answer: 1, explanation: "He proclaims anyone can climb while sawing the rung beneath him above rungs already broken, so the point is the gap between the rhetoric of opportunity and the removal of its means. The ladders option is a meta-comment, not the message. The not-trying option blames the worker, when the cartoon blames the sawer. The no-help option is the reverse of what is shown.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-012", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-grc1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: GRC1, alt: "A well-dressed figure near the top of a ladder labelled OPPORTUNITY saws off the rung beneath his feet; the lower rungs are already broken; a worker at the foot of the ladder reaches upward.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "The rungs already broken beneath the figure most directly imply that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the ladder was merely built badly to begin with", "the worker has climbed before and chosen to descend", "the means of rising are being removed even as climbing is urged", "opportunity is steadily widening for all"], answer: 2, explanation: "Broken rungs beneath a figure cutting another show ascent disappearing while the language of opportunity continues. The built-badly option misses the deliberate sawing, reading a structural fault for a chosen removal. The descended option invents a backstory. The widening option is the reverse.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-013", genre: "graphic", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-grc1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: GRC1, alt: "A well-dressed figure at the top of a ladder labelled OPPORTUNITY saws the rung beneath himself while saying anyone can climb up.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "The cartoon's attitude toward the figure at the top is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["neutral and merely factual", "admiring of his success", "fearful of him", "satirical, exposing the gap between his words and his act"], answer: 3, explanation: "Pairing the cheerful claim with the act of destroying the rungs is pointed mockery of a contradiction. The neutral option ignores that edge. The admiring option mistakes the target. The fearful option finds an emotion the cartoon does not show.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-014", genre: "graphic", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-grc2", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: GRC2, alt: "A large factory labelled OUR FACTORY pours out a big cloud of smoke labelled EMISSIONS. Beside it an owner points proudly at a tiny potted sapling labelled OFFSET and says we are going green.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "The cartoon most strongly suggests that the company's environmental effort is...", format: "single_best", options: ["tiny in proportion to the harm it goes on causing", "more than enough to cancel its emissions", "unrelated to the factory beside it", "quietly very effective"], answer: 0, explanation: "One small sapling set against a factory and a vast plume makes the gesture token beside ongoing harm. The cancel option is the reverse. The unrelated option ignores that it is the same company. The effective option is contradicted by the scale.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-015", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-grc2", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: GRC2, alt: "A large smoking factory labelled EMISSIONS dwarfs a tiny potted sapling labelled OFFSET that the proud owner points to.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "The difference in size between the smoke and the sapling is used to imply that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the factory has stopped emitting altogether", "the offset is a token gesture, dwarfed by the emissions that continue", "the sapling will in time grow into a forest", "the owner secretly dislikes the factory"], answer: 1, explanation: "Vast emissions against a minute offset make the point about proportion. The stopped option is the reverse, the smoke still pours. The forest option reads in a future growth the cartoon does not show. The dislikes option invents a motive.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-016", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-grc2", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: GRC2, alt: "An owner points proudly at a tiny sapling labelled OFFSET while a large factory behind pours out emissions, claiming the company is going green.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "Which claim does the cartoon most directly undercut?", format: "single_best", options: ["that growing plants can absorb carbon", "that factories manufacture goods", "that the company's small gesture offsets its continuing pollution", "that the owner is pleased with the company"], answer: 2, explanation: "Dwarfing the sapling beside the smoke attacks the claim that the token gesture balances the pollution. It does not dispute that plants absorb carbon or that factories make goods, and the owner is plainly pleased.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-013", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-po3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: PO3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The detail that the stone did its work 'when I was not listening' chiefly implies that the deeper truth...", format: "single_best", options: ["announced itself suddenly and unmistakably", "was done quietly, unnoticed while he attended to the obvious sound", "was pointed out to him by someone else", "could be grasped only by deliberately ignoring the river"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options read the phrase as incidental inattention and two as an external or sudden revelation. The stone works unnoticed while he listens to the obvious noise, so the truth surfaces incidentally, the unnoticed-while-attending reading; the deliberately-ignoring twin makes inattention a chosen method, where the poem makes it accidental. The someone-else and announced-suddenly options supply a teacher or a loud revelation the poem withholds.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-013", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-sb1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: SB1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's tone throughout is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["alarmed and partisan", "mocking of those who worry about screens", "measured, weighing rival explanations without settling on one", "uncertain to the point of having no view"], answer: 2, explanation: "He sets competing causes side by side and resists a verdict, which is measured. The alarmed option misreads the calm. The mocking option invents a target. The no-view option is the trap, since being measured is not the same as having no view, and he clearly holds that one cause should not be inferred.", difficulty: "easy", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-hard-001", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsa", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSA, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The 'treachery' of the photograph consists chiefly in the fact that...", format: "single_best", options: ["it cannot soften and recompose itself as a remembered face does", "its fixity makes it a more reliable witness than memory, and so the harder to doubt", "its permanence tempts us to trust a mere surface as though it were the living past", "it absorbs the moods of the viewer until it ceases to be a record"], answer: 2, explanation: "All four engage the photograph and memory, so none is off-topic. The treachery is that its permanence tempts us to take a surface for the living past, the trust-the-surface reading; the more-reliable twin sits in the same family but the passage never ranks it above memory, only says it keeps a surface. The cannot-recompose option is true yet not the treachery, and the absorbs-the-viewer's-moods option borrows memory's trait and pins it wrongly on the photograph.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-002", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-hsa", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSA, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "If 'fixed' in 'fixed at an instant the sitter did not choose' were replaced, which word would best preserve the author's sense?", format: "single_best", options: ["arrested", "immured", "petrified", "obtruded"], answer: 0, explanation: "Fixed at an instant means stopped and held in time, which is arrested. Immured means walled in or imprisoned, a spatial confinement rather than a stopping of time. Petrified means turned to stone or frozen by fear, importing a rigidity or terror the line does not carry. Obtruded means thrust forward where unwanted, a different idea entirely. The rarer words are set to tempt a guess; only arrested matches the precise sense.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-003", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-hsa", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSA, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The writer's central claim about old photographs is that they...", format: "single_best", options: ["keep a moment so faithfully that they expose memory as the inferior record", "keep the exterior of a moment while withholding the lived duration that gave it meaning", "are companions that take on our changing moods over time", "grow more poignant precisely because, unlike memory, they fade"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options say what the photograph preserves and two compare it with memory, so the reader fixes the axis first. It keeps the exterior while losing the lived duration, the surface-not-duration reading; the expose-memory twin overstates into a ranking the passage avoids. The companions option lends the photograph memory's mood-taking, and the they-fade option is simply false, since not fading is the photograph's defining trait.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-004", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsa", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSA, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In the final sentence, 'the continuance of the moment beyond its own border' refers to...", format: "single_best", options: ["the physical edge of the printed photograph", "the frame within which the sitter was posed", "the threshold of memory, beyond which the image cannot reach back", "the edge of the captured instant in time, past which the moment cannot extend"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options read the border as something physical and two as something abstract, so the reader must choose. It is the temporal edge of the instant, past which the moment does not continue, the lived-time reading; the memory-threshold twin is abstract but wrong, since the longing is for the moment's own continuance, not a reach by memory. The printed-edge and posing-frame options take the border literally.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-hard-005", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-hsb", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSB, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The distinction on which the whole argument rests is between...", format: "single_best", options: ["democracy and expertise as competing systems of government", "the equal right to hold an opinion and the unequal reliability of opinions once held", "citizens and engineers as classes of people", "questions that have answers and questions that do not"], answer: 1, explanation: "The hinge is the equal right to a view set against the unequal worth of views as guides to truth. The rival-systems option misframes the piece, which defends expertise within democracy. The classes option seizes on the example's people rather than the right-versus-reliability point. The answerable option names a consequence the argument reaches, not the distinction it rests on.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-006", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsb", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSB, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "On the writer's view, treating every opinion as of equal weight is defensible when the question concerns...", format: "single_best", options: ["the technical means of reaching a goal", "the structural safety of a particular bridge", "any matter on which experts happen to disagree", "the ends a society chooses to pursue"], answer: 3, explanation: "The democratic instinct is sound for ends, the values pursued, but incoherent for means. The technical-means and bridge options are exactly the means-type questions where it is incoherent. The experts-disagree option adds a condition the passage never makes, since disagreement does not make equal weight defensible.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-007", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-hsb", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSB, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which of the following, if true, would most weaken the writer's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["Most citizens are content to defer to engineers on technical questions", "Societies do tend to value their chosen ends above the means of reaching them", "On technical questions, equally qualified experts disagree about as often as laypeople do", "Democracies, given time, usually arrive at sound decisions"], answer: 2, explanation: "The argument depends on experts being more reliable on technical questions, so equal qualified disagreement collapses that reliability and the means-ends distinction built on it. The deference option is neutral. The ends option supports one half. The good-decisions option sounds pro-democracy but never touches the reliability premise.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-008", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-hsb", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSB, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, 'conflates' most nearly means...", format: "single_best", options: ["wrongly merges into one two things that should be kept distinct", "carefully distinguishes between two things", "weighs two things against each other", "openly rejects one of two things"], answer: 0, explanation: "The principle treats as identical two things that ought to be kept apart, that is, it wrongly merges them. The distinguishes option is the opposite. The weighs option is not merging. The rejects option describes dismissal, not conflation.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-hard-009", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-hsc", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSC, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is principally a warning against...", format: "single_best", options: ["the pursuit of wealth and connection", "the practice of keeping careful accounts", "treating progress as one-directional and mistaking the measurable for what matters", "technological advancement of every kind"], answer: 2, explanation: "It attacks both the single-road picture of progress and the assumption that only the measurable matters. The wealth option names mere examples of ambiguous advances. The accounts option is wrong, since the fault is losing the goods while keeping the accounts impeccably. The technology option is never the target.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-010", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsc", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSC, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say a society 'mistakes its instruments for its purposes' is to say that it...", format: "single_best", options: ["lacks the tools required to measure what matters", "comes to value its measures over the ends those measures were meant to serve", "keeps deliberately false accounts", "grows richer without growing more anxious"], answer: 1, explanation: "Instruments are the measures, purposes the ends, so the error is prizing the measure over the end. The lacks-tools option is wrong, since it keeps its accounts impeccably. The deliberately-false option misreads a sincere misvaluing as fraud. The richer option is unrelated.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-011", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-hsc", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSC, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The writer's attitude toward 'progress' is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["wholly dismissive of any improvement", "uncritically enthusiastic", "entirely indifferent", "sceptical of its simple, one-directional sense while granting the advances are real"], answer: 3, explanation: "He calls the advances real and not illusory yet doubts their sum points one way, which is qualified scepticism. The dismissive option ignores that concession. The enthusiastic option is the reverse. The indifferent option misses his evident concern.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-012", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsc", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSC, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best illustrates the passage's central warning?", format: "single_best", options: ["a hospital that improves its measured waiting times while patients leave feeling less cared for", "a hospital that improves both its waiting times and its patients' sense of being cared for", "a hospital too poorly funded to measure its waiting times", "a hospital that ignores its waiting times entirely"], answer: 0, explanation: "A measured good rises while an unmeasured good is lost, exactly the instruments-for-purposes error. The both-improve option shows no loss, so no warning. The poorly-funded option is a different problem, an inability to measure. The ignores option is the opposite error, neglecting measures rather than over-valuing them.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-hard-013", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-hsd", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSD, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The cartographer chiefly figures...", format: "single_best", options: ["the painstaking craft that produces a beautiful object", "the real hazards of crossing uncharted marshland", "those who give us flattering falsehoods because we would rather have them than the truth", "well-meaning guides whose errors come from honest incompetence"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options read the cartographer as one who misleads us and two as craft or literal danger. He draws the world it wished and we ask it of him, so he gives flattering falsehoods we prefer, the wanted-falsehood reading; the honest-incompetence twin shares the misleading frame but the poem makes the falseness knowing and demanded, not a mistake. The craft option seizes on the maps being beautiful, and the hazards option reads the marsh literally.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-014", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hsd", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSD, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The final stanza implies that, from those who chart the world for us, people most want...", format: "single_best", options: ["maps beautiful enough to be admired in themselves", "a firm place to stand, even where the truth would offer none", "maps confident enough to remove all doubt about the way ahead", "the unvarnished truth about the terrain, whatever it costs"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options are forms of reassurance and two are honesty or beauty. The close asks not the truth but somewhere firm to stand, so it is a footing the truth would not give, the firm-place reading; the remove-all-doubt twin overstates it into total certainty, where the poem asks only for a place to stand among the signs. The truth option is the opposite of what is wanted, and the beautiful option is a feature, not the want.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-015", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-hsd", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSD, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The speaker's attitude toward the cartographer is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["wholly condemnatory of a dishonest craftsman", "warmly approving of a craftsman who gives people what they want", "torn between condemning the maps and admiring their beauty", "critical of the deception, yet understanding the need that demands it"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options are one-sided and two hold opposed feelings together. The maps mislead and are cursed, yet the close grants why people want them, so the speaker is critical but understanding, the criticism-with-sympathy reading; the torn-by-beauty twin keeps the mixed feeling but locates it in aesthetics, where the poem's tension is between the deception and the human need. The condemnatory and approving options each take only one side.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hard-016", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-hsd", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HSD, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The phrase 'all honest swamp, no promise in the lines' describes a map that is...", format: "single_best", options: ["honest about the terrain, and therefore offering no reassurance", "carelessly drawn, with rough and broken lines", "so faithful to every flaw that it is useless for planning a route", "showing nothing but swampland from edge to edge"], answer: 0, explanation: "Two options read the phrase as the honest map and two as careless or literal. All honest swamp, no promise means it tells the unflattering truth and so offers no comfort, the no-reassurance reading; the useless-for-planning twin misreads no promise as no utility, though an honest map is in fact more useful, only less comforting. The careless option confuses honesty with poor work, and the all-swamp option reads it literally.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-001", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the present instant can be isolated if we attend to it carefully enough", "memory and anticipation are unreliable and distort the present", "music is the only experience that reveals the true structure of time", "the present we experience already contains the just-past and the anticipated next, and is not a single durationless instant"], answer: 3, explanation: "The whole passage builds the claim that the now is thickened, holding the trailing note and leaning toward the coming one. The bare instant is precisely what the author denies, and music is an illustration rather than the point.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-002", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of consciousness not occupying time \"as a body occupies a chair\" is used to deny that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the body and the mind are governed by the same laws", "the mind sits within a time that exists independently of it", "time can be measured by physical instruments", "consciousness is located in a particular place"], answer: 1, explanation: "A body in a chair is contained by something already there. Denying that analogy denies that consciousness merely sits inside a pre-given time, which fits the claim that it itself holds open the span within which objects appear.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-003", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-vh1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that stripping away the \"fringe\" makes melody collapse into unrelated instants functions in the argument as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a concession to the opposing view", "an admission that the author cannot prove the main claim", "an example chosen only because music is pleasant", "a step showing that without the trailing past and leaning future even hearing a phrase would be impossible"], answer: 3, explanation: "The collapse of melody is offered as what would follow if the fringe were removed; since we do hear melodies, the fringe must be there. It supports the thesis rather than conceding or merely decorating it.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-004", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-vh1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "As the passage uses it, the not-yet being \"sketched in advance by the very shape of what we have heard\" most nearly means...", format: "single_best", options: ["an anticipatory openness to what is about to come, shaped by what came before", "a deliberate prediction reached by conscious reasoning", "a vivid memory of the immediate past", "a lingering after-image of a vanished sound"], answer: 0, explanation: "The phrase describes expectation built into present experience by its prior shape, not a reasoned forecast and not a backward-looking memory or trace.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-005", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The central claim of the passage is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["we should stop saving for the future because the future self is a stranger", "personal identity is an illusion with no practical consequences", "if identity is a matter of degrees of psychological connection, it may not be the thing that grounds concern for our future", "memory is the only thing that makes a person the same over time"], answer: 2, explanation: "The argument moves from identity as graded connection to the unsettling suggestion that identity, so understood, may not be what justifies self-concern. The stronger claims about illusion or about not saving overshoot what the text says.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-006", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author calls the discomfort the view produces \"instructive\" because it...", format: "single_best", options: ["proves that people are too attached to their own comfort", "shows that the view must be false, since it feels wrong", "reveals that something we treated as bedrock may not survive scrutiny", "suggests the argument should be abandoned"], answer: 2, explanation: "The discomfort teaches us something: that an assumption we leaned on, identity as the ground of self-concern, may not hold. The author does not treat the feeling as a refutation.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-007", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-vh2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The final sentence extends the argument by suggesting that...", format: "single_best", options: ["if connection rather than identity grounds concern for our future self, similar connections to others could ground obligations to them", "we owe nothing to our future selves", "obligations to others always outweigh obligations to ourselves", "psychological connections are too weak to ground any obligation"], answer: 0, explanation: "Having relocated what matters from identity to connection, the author notes that connection also reaches outward to others, so the same basis would extend obligations to them in lesser measure.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-008", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-vh2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, \"identity admits of degree\" most nearly means that identity...", format: "single_best", options: ["must be earned through effort over time", "can hold more or less fully rather than being all or nothing", "is granted by other people rather than possessed", "changes only at fixed thresholds"], answer: 1, explanation: "To admit of degree is to come in gradations; the passage contrasts this with the all-or-nothing assumption behind a sharp yes or no to whether a future person is you.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-009", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly maintains that...", format: "single_best", options: ["originality in art is impossible to define", "forgeries are usually easy to detect with the right instruments", "the appearance of a painting is all that anyone really cares about", "a work's value depends partly on its origin and achievement, not only on how it looks"], answer: 3, explanation: "The author argues that what we value includes the work as a made achievement at a particular moment, which the perfect forgery lacks despite an identical surface.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-010", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-vh3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author answers the view that the forgery \"must be\" as good mainly by...", format: "single_best", options: ["agreeing that the two are equal but regretting it", "rejecting its premise that a painting's value is exhausted by how it looks", "claiming the forgery can always be detected eventually", "showing the forger acted dishonestly"], answer: 1, explanation: "The opposing view rests on the premise that nothing beyond appearance matters; the author denies that premise rather than the detectability of the fraud or the morality of the forger.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-011", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Describing the forgery as \"parasitic\" most strongly implies that it...", format: "single_best", options: ["was made without any skill", "will physically damage the original over time", "is worth more than the original to collectors", "draws its aim from the original rather than achieving anything of its own"], answer: 3, explanation: "Parasitic here means it reaches only toward another painting; its point is borrowed from the original. It plainly required great skill, so lack of skill is wrong.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-012", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-vh3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's attitude toward those who call the two paintings equal is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["measured but firmly corrective", "openly scornful and mocking", "admiring and persuaded", "indifferent and detached"], answer: 0, explanation: "The author treats the opposing view seriously and answers it by saying it forgets what we were valuing: a correction delivered without ridicule, so measured but corrective.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-001", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-hd1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's irony depends chiefly on...", format: "single_best", options: ["her framing a self-serving division as an impartial principle, without seeing the contradiction", "her composing herself where her sister breaks down, and taking composure for virtue", "her knowingly dressing her greed as fairness, trusting that no one will notice", "her envying her sister's freedom to show open feeling"], answer: 0, explanation: "Two options turn on her self-image against her conduct and two on the contrast with her sister's feeling, so the reader picks the axis. The irony is that she dresses a self-serving split as a fair principle without noticing, the unwitting reading; the knowingly-dresses twin is wrong, since she plainly believes herself the reasonable one. The composure and envy options seize the emotional contrast, real enough but not where the irony sits.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-002", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hd1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In calling Clara's weeping 'its own kind of advantage', the narrator unwittingly reveals that she...", format: "single_best", options: ["regards open emotion as a weakness beneath her", "believes Clara's tears are calculated and admires the cunning", "reads others' feeling as manoeuvre while never suspecting her own principle of being one", "secretly wishes she could weep as easily as Clara"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options concern how she reads tears and two her attitude to emotion at large. She treats others' feeling as a tactic yet exempts her own fair principle from the same suspicion, the self-exemption reading; the admires-the-cunning twin shares the tactic reading but is wrong, since she disdains rather than admires. The weakness and wish-to-weep options speak to her view of emotion, not the asymmetry the remark exposes.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-003", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-hd1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's tone is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["briskly matter-of-fact, presenting her conduct as plain common sense", "complacently self-justifying, untroubled by any doubt", "defensive, betraying unease beneath the composure", "quietly remorseful about the division"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options read her as untroubled and two as inwardly uneasy, so the call is fine. She is pleased with herself and busy justifying, the complacent reading; the matter-of-fact twin is close but understates the self-approval, since she is not merely neutral but gratified. The defensive and remorseful options find an unease or regret the passage never shows.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-004", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-hd2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The line 'A broken clock is honest twice' is used chiefly to...", format: "single_best", options: ["set the clock's small accidental truth against the larger comforting lie the family keeps", "praise the rare honesty of admitting that time has stopped", "claim a stopped clock is more useful than a working one", "honour the grandfather who first wound the clock"], answer: 0, explanation: "Two options turn on the honesty theme and two read the line literally or as tribute. A stopped clock is right twice a day, a trivial accidental truth set against the lie that nothing has moved, the accidental-truth reading; the praises-honesty twin inverts the irony, since the family does not admit the truth but keeps the lie. The more-useful option reads it literally, and the grandfather option makes it a tribute to a person.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-005", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hd2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem suggests the family keeps the stopped clock because...", format: "single_best", options: ["it remains a handsome object worth displaying", "it still keeps the hour well enough to be useful", "to keep it is to avoid admitting that time, and loss, have moved on", "they cannot bring themselves to discard a thing the grandfather once tended"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options give practical reasons and two emotional ones, so the reader picks the axis. Taking it down would grant the morning it stopped, so keeping it avoids admitting that time has moved on, the denial reading; the cannot-discard twin shares the emotional frame but makes it sentiment for the grandfather's object, where the poem makes it a refusal to face the passage of time. The handsome-object and still-keeps-time options are practical, the latter also false, since it has not found the hour in years.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-006", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-hd2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The speaker's tone is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["sharply critical of the family's refusal to face facts", "coolly detached, merely describing the clock on the shelf", "gently nostalgic, fond of the old clock and what it stands for", "rueful and self-implicating, counting himself among those who prefer the lie"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options keep the speaker at a distance and two place him inside the feeling. What they point me to draws him in, so he is rueful and self-implicating, the inside reading; the nostalgic twin keeps the warmth but makes it fondness for the clock, where the poem is rueful about a shared self-deception. The critical option stands outside and accuses, and the detached option ignores the evident feeling.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-007", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-hd3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main objection to success memoirs is that they...", format: "single_best", options: ["are written chiefly to make their authors money", "give advice that is positively harmful to follow", "misremember the habits that led to success", "draw their lessons from a sample selected by the very outcome they claim to explain"], answer: 3, explanation: "Only winners write, so the sample is chosen by the outcome and habits shared with unseen losers explain nothing. The money option targets motive. The harmful option overstates, the advice is unsupported, not damaging. The misremember option is the near-miss, but the flaw is the selected sample, not faulty memory, since a vividly accurate memory of a shared habit still explains nothing.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-008", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hd3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'chosen by the very outcome it claims to explain' identifies the error of...", format: "single_best", options: ["preferring vivid personal stories to dry statistics", "confusing a cause with its effect", "reasoning only from cases that already turned out well", "ignoring the testimony of acknowledged experts"], answer: 2, explanation: "The sample is built from successes, so it is the survivorship error of looking only at cases that already succeeded. The stories option misnames the fault. The cause-effect option is a different fallacy, adjacent but not selection by outcome. The experts option is unrelated.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-009", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-hd3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The final sentence most directly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["habits play no real part in success at all", "a habit found equally among those who failed cannot account for the winning", "successful people rarely recall their own habits accurately", "vivid memories are generally unreliable"], answer: 1, explanation: "A habit shared by winners and losers explains nothing about winning, however vividly recalled. The no-part option overstates, since the passage denies only that a shared habit distinguishes winning, not that habits never matter. The recall and vivid-memory options shift the point from logic to memory.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-010", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-hd4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's saying his memory became 'usefully uncertain' is best understood as...", format: "single_best", options: ["evidence that he had never truly known who took the money", "his honestly losing confidence in the memory as the years passed", "proof that he had forgotten the incident until the dismissal brought it back", "his reshaping a clear memory into doubt because the doubt served his interest"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options say the doubt was genuine and two that he never really knew or had forgotten, so the reader weighs the kind of uncertainty. He knew as surely as his own name and then usefully revised that, the motivated-doubt reading; the honestly-lost-confidence twin shares the doubt but strips the word usefully of its force. The never-knew and forgot options deny the certainty the passage gives him at the start.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-011", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-hd4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator is best characterised as a man who...", format: "single_best", options: ["is unaware that his silence is wrong", "sees his own cowardice clearly and yields to it all the same", "is paralysed by a genuine conflict of loyalties he cannot resolve", "is pressured into silence by the under-manager"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options grant that he understands his failure and two deny it, locating the cause in ignorance or coercion. He sees the cowardice exactly and gives in anyway, the lucid-cowardice reading; the paralysed-by-conflict twin shares the awareness but softens it into helplessness, where the text shows self-interested choice. The unaware and pressured options are both contradicted, since he knows the clerk is innocent and acts from his own advancement.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-hd-012", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-hd4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: HD4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narration's relationship to the narrator's own conduct is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["defensive, working to justify his silence", "ruefully reflective, dwelling on the episode with soft regret", "unsparingly confessional, naming his evasions without excusing them", "detached, reporting the events without judgement"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options read the voice as self-aware and two as defensive or cool. He states the worst of himself, the revised memory and the handshake he meant, without seeking exoneration, the unsparing-confession reading; the ruefully-reflective twin is close but too soft, since he does not merely regret but lays the fault bare. The defensive and detached options miss either the candour or the moral weight.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-001", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-md1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central insight is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["returning to a childhood home is bound to disappoint", "the town's loss of grandeur is what saddens her, now that she sees it plainly", "what she grieves is not the town but the child for whom it was once everything", "travel spoils one's contentment with smaller places"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options say what she grieves and two offer a general truth, so the reader must choose the level. She grieves the child for whom the town was once the whole world, not the town, the lost-self reading; the loss-of-grandeur twin keeps the focus on the town, which the passage says has not changed. The bound-to-disappoint and travel-spoils options generalise into maxims the passage never asserts.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-002", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-md1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of the years having 'let the air out of it' attributes the town's diminishment to...", format: "single_best", options: ["a change in her, who has grown and seen larger things", "a real decline in the town during her years away", "a trick of memory that exaggerates how grand the town once was", "the neglect of the town by those who left it"], answer: 0, explanation: "Two options place the cause in her and two in the town, so the reader picks the side. The diminishment is in her, grown and widely travelled, the changed-perceiver reading; the trick-of-memory twin also locates it in her mind but wrongly, blaming a false memory rather than her real growth. The decline and neglect options put the change in the town, which the passage denies, the town has not shrunk.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-003", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-md1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's tone is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["faintly bitter that the town has shrunk into something ordinary", "wistful, mourning an inevitable loss that blames no one", "nostalgic, warmed by fond memories of the town", "coolly analytical about the workings of memory"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options are soft-toned and two sharp or cool, so the call is a shade. It is wistful over a blameless, inevitable loss, growing up; the warm-nostalgia twin shares the gentleness but misses the disappointment, since the feeling is sad, not fond. The bitter option finds a grievance the passage refuses, and the analytical option is too cool for so felt a reflection.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-004", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-md2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem most strongly suggests that...", format: "single_best", options: ["we owe it to those who come after to provide what we ourselves will not enjoy", "the wise accept that their own labour will, in time, benefit chiefly themselves", "old age is best spent on quiet, undemanding pastimes", "patience is rewarded for those who are willing to wait long enough"], answer: 0, explanation: "Two options concern why he plants and two draw a general moral. He plants what he will not sit beneath, repaying the debt of every shade sat down, so it is provision for those after us, the for-others reading; the benefit-themselves twin keeps the why-plant frame but reverses it, since he plainly will not benefit. The old-age and patience options are generic morals the poem does not support, the latter false, since he is not waiting for his own reward.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-005", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-md2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "'The debt of every shade sat down' refers to...", format: "single_best", options: ["the tiredness of one who has rested too long in the shade", "the money owed for trees an earlier owner had planted", "the obligation we incur by having enjoyed what earlier hands provided", "the gratitude we feel toward those whose work we have benefited from"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options read the debt as an obligation or feeling and two read it literally or financially. Having sat in shade others planted creates an obligation discharged by planting for those to come, the obligation reading; the gratitude twin keeps the owing-for-benefit frame but makes it a feeling, where the poem makes it a debt repaid forward. The tiredness option reads sat down literally, and the money option makes the debt financial.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-006", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-md2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD2, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The tone of the poem is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["faintly mournful that he will not live to enjoy the tree", "quietly reverent toward a selfless, forward-looking act", "warmly affectionate toward a contented old gardener", "briskly practical about the ordinary work of planting"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two options are warm-reverent and two are mournful or matter-of-fact. The selfless planting is treated with calm respect, the reverence-for-the-act reading; the affectionate twin keeps the warmth but aims it at the gardener's contentment, where the poem honours the act and its principle. The mournful option misreads the steady tone as sorrow, and the practical option flattens the poem's gravity.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-007", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-md3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main objection to the idea that reading lengthens life is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["a shared cause, prosperity, may produce both the bookshops and the longer lives", "the study surveyed too few towns to be reliable", "bookshops are in fact closing in most towns", "lifespans cannot be measured with any accuracy"], answer: 0, explanation: "The author proposes a confounder, prosperity, that buys both bookshops and longevity. The too-few-towns option makes it about sample size. The closing option is irrelevant. The measurement option misnames the difficulty, which is causal, not metric.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-008", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-md3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Calling the bookshop 'a symptom of the same prosperity' casts it as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a cause of the town's good health", "a drain on the town's resources", "the reason the town became prosperous", "a sign of the wealth that independently lengthens life"], answer: 3, explanation: "A symptom indicates an underlying condition, so the bookshop signals the prosperity that extends life by other means. The cause option is the reverse of symptom. The drain option is unrelated. The reason option reverses the direction, since prosperity produces the bookshop, not the other way round.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-009", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-md3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD3, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is best summarised as a caution that...", format: "single_best", options: ["only wealthy towns can ever be healthy", "studies of this kind should never be believed", "an apparent cause may be only a by-product of a deeper common factor", "reading confers no benefit of any kind"], answer: 2, explanation: "Watch for a confounder behind a correlation. The only-wealthy option overstates. The never-believed option is too sweeping. The no-benefit option is wrong, since the passage denies only the lifespan claim, not every benefit of reading.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-010", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-md4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Feeding the gulls is best understood as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a continued communion with his late wife, in the only form still open to him", "an attempt to win the goodwill of the townspeople", "a way of keeping his grief at bay by filling the empty mornings", "a quiet defiance of those who call him a nuisance"], answer: 0, explanation: "Two options read the act as about his loss and two as facing the town, so the reader chooses. It is communion with the wife who loved the birds, the only language still open to him; the keep-grief-at-bay twin also concerns his loss but inverts it, since he continues a conversation rather than fending grief off. The goodwill and defiance options make it about the town, yet he says nothing to any of them.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-011", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-md4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly contrasts...", format: "single_best", options: ["the kindness of the children with the unkindness of the adults", "the gulls' usefulness with their reputation as vermin", "the town's noisy opinions with the old man's deliberate silence", "the town's several explanations with a private meaning none of them reaches"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options seize surface details and two set the town against the man, so the reader picks the real axis. The contrast is the town's guesses against a private meaning none of them reaches, the guesses-miss reading; the noise-against-silence twin is close but shallower, naming the form rather than the gap in understanding. The children-adults and vermin options fasten on minor notes, not the contrast the passage builds.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-012", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-md4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's treatment of the old man is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["gently amused by the town's competing opinions", "detached, simply recording the scene and the gossip", "tender, guarding a grief the town has misread", "warmly admiring of his steadfast daily devotion"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options are warm and two cool, so the call is a shade. The narration tenderly guards a grief the town misjudges, the protective reading; the warm-admiration twin shares the warmth but misnames it, since the feeling is protective of his loss, not admiration of a routine. The amused and detached options miss the evident sympathy in the only language still open to him.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-013", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-md5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["economic downturns cannot be predicted by anyone", "a forecast that no events could prove wrong is empty as a claim about the world", "pundits are usually right about downturns in the end", "economic forecasting is a precise and reliable science"], answer: 1, explanation: "An unfalsifiable forecast tells us nothing about the world. The cannot-be-predicted option overstates, since the passage faults this kind of forecast, not all prediction. The usually-right and precise-science options are the reverse of its point.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-014", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-md5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing sentence implies that a useful prediction must...", format: "single_best", options: ["always turn out to be true", "be made by a properly qualified expert", "specify conditions under which it would count as false", "be kept vague enough to remain safe"], answer: 2, explanation: "The test is whether it could have come false, so a useful prediction names what would disconfirm it. The always-true option misreads falsifiability. The expert option is about credentials, not the test. The vague option is the vice the passage exposes.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-015", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-md5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, 'disconfirm' most nearly means...", format: "single_best", options: ["confirm beyond doubt", "predict in advance", "state more emphatically", "show to be false"], answer: 3, explanation: "A forecast no events could disconfirm is one nothing could show to be false. The confirm option is the opposite. The predict and emphatically options have nothing to do with falsification.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-016", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-md6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD6, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "Naming the road 'Meadow View' is presented as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a practical label to help drivers find the road", "a sign that the meadow will be restored in time", "a small tribute meant to soften the loss of the meadow", "a hollow gesture, naming in tar the very thing the paving destroyed"], answer: 3, explanation: "Two options read the name against the loss and two read it as practical or hopeful. As if a word in tar could keep a promise grass once knew, so the name is an empty gesture for what was destroyed, the hollow reading; the tribute twin shares the name-and-loss frame but makes it a sincere consolation, where the poem's irony makes it empty. The label option reads it as navigation, and the restored option supplies a hope the poem denies.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-017", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-md6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD6, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The tone of the poem is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["wry irony laid over a quiet grief for what was lost", "bittersweet nostalgia for a vanished rural past", "open anger at those who paved the meadow", "flat, factual reporting of a road and its name"], answer: 0, explanation: "Two options are sad-toned and two are angry or neutral. It mocks the sign while mourning the meadow, so wry irony lies over quiet grief, the ironic-elegiac reading; the nostalgia twin keeps the sadness but softens the sharp irony into warm looking-back. The anger option overstates the wryness, and the factual option ignores both the feeling and the irony.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-md-018", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-md6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: MD6, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The line 'The sign is honest, in its way' means the sign...", format: "single_best", options: ["gives accurate directions to the meadow", "was put up by scrupulous officials", "is honest only by accident, since in naming the meadow it records its absence", "openly admits that the meadow was destroyed"], answer: 2, explanation: "Two options read the honesty as accidental or frank and two read it literally. It tells you what is not there, so it is honest only by accident in marking an absence, the accidental reading; the openly-admits twin keeps the honesty frame but makes it a frank confession, where the sign records the loss unwittingly, not as an admission. The directions and officials options take honest literally, as accuracy or the integrity of people.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-013", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the boat club is mistaken to speak of the boat as the same one", "a boat cannot really be the same once all its parts have been replaced", "personal identity is securely grounded in the physical stuff of the body", "the sameness of both boats and persons may lie in continuous maintenance rather than in any enduring material"], answer: 3, explanation: "The re-planked boat is used to locate identity in an unbroken practice of upkeep, and the author then extends this to persons whose cells are likewise replaced, so sameness is a continuity of maintenance rather than a possessed substance.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-014", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-vh4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The example of the re-planked boat functions in the argument to...", format: "single_best", options: ["make a claim about persons more acceptable by first establishing it in a case we accept without discomfort", "prove that boats and persons are identical in every relevant respect", "show that the boat club misunderstands its own history", "concede that material continuity is what identity really requires"], answer: 0, explanation: "The boat is the easy case we grant readily, and the author leverages that acceptance to press the harder, resisted claim about ourselves, so it is an analogical lever rather than a proof of full identity or a concession.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-015", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author suggests we \"resist the comparison\" because...", format: "single_best", options: ["we believe boats and persons obey entirely different laws", "we doubt that our cells are in fact replaced over time", "we would rather our continued existence depended on something we have than on something we keep doing", "we find the boat club's claim to sameness obviously false"], answer: 2, explanation: "The closing sentence states the resistance directly: we prefer sameness to rest on a possessed stuff rather than on an ongoing activity of upkeep that could in principle lapse.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-016", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-vh4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, \"upkeep\" most nearly refers to...", format: "single_best", options: ["the original material from which a thing was first made", "the expense of maintaining a costly object", "the ongoing activity of repair and replacement that sustains a thing over time", "the reputation a thing acquires through being famous"], answer: 2, explanation: "Upkeep names the continuous practice of repair that carries the boat, and the person, forward, not the expense, the origins, or the fame of the thing.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-017", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-vh5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage most strongly reveals that the narrator...", format: "single_best", options: ["extracts a steady return for his help while believing that he gives freely", "gave generously and was genuinely wronged by an ungrateful brother", "regrets having taken his brother in at all", "has quietly forgiven his brother's sudden departure"], answer: 0, explanation: "He claims to keep no ledger and to ask nothing, yet itemises the deference, the car, the television and his mother's good opinion he collected, so his giving is transactional beneath a generous self-image.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-018", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The detail that the brother was \"strangely slow\" to offer acknowledgement most strongly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the brother was simply forgetful and a little inconsiderate", "the brother sensed the price attached to the help and withheld the gratitude demanded of him", "the brother had not in fact been helped at all", "the narrator had genuinely asked for nothing and was puzzled"], answer: 1, explanation: "From the narrator's slanted account we infer the brother felt the conditions on the help and declined to perform the gratitude it was meant to buy, which the narrator can only read as a defect in others.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-019", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-vh5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's tone is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["detached and coolly factual", "openly cruel and domineering", "humble and quietly wounded", "aggrieved and self-congratulatory at once"], answer: 3, explanation: "He congratulates himself on giving without a ledger while nursing a grievance at the missing thanks, blending self-praise with complaint rather than humility or open cruelty.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-020", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The final sentence chiefly works to...", format: "single_best", options: ["offer a fair general observation about human pride", "complete the portrait of a man who reframes his own conditions as the failings of those he helps", "reveal the narrator's sudden insight into his own behaviour", "express genuine sympathy for people who cannot accept help"], answer: 1, explanation: "The remark that some people cannot bear to be helped turns the brother's escape from a priced generosity into a flaw in others, sealing the irony rather than showing insight or sympathy.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-021", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-vh6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH6, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The phrase \"the patient committee of the past\" chiefly figures the past as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a council that preserves names against forgetting", "a panel of judges who decide what shall be remembered", "a group of mourners gathered at the harbour", "an unhurried, impersonal force that wears memory away by slow collective action"], answer: 3, explanation: "Committee personifies the slow, faceless action of time and tide that erodes the carved name, and patient stresses its unhurried inevitability, the opposite of preservation.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-022", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-vh6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH6, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The tone of the final stanza is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["tender and quietly desolate", "bitter and accusing", "serene and consoled", "ironic and detached"], answer: 0, explanation: "The speaker still returns to trace the vanished name with a cold thumb and confronts the loss without comfort, which is tender yet desolate rather than bitter, consoled, or detached.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-023", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH6, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The line \"I read the absence, not the name\" most strongly suggests that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the carved letters were never legible to begin with", "the speaker has forgotten how to read the inscription", "what remains to the speaker is the felt fact of loss rather than the person once recorded", "the sea has improved the appearance of the stone"], answer: 2, explanation: "Where the name has worn to nothing, what the speaker now perceives is the absence itself, the loss made present, rather than the person the letters once named.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-024", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH6, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem chiefly explores...", format: "single_best", options: ["the consoling permanence that monuments give to the dead", "the importance of choosing durable materials for a memorial", "how time erodes both a memorial and the speaker's certainty about what it preserves", "the speaker's anger at the indifference of the sea"], answer: 2, explanation: "The wearing-away of the name runs parallel to the speaker's growing doubt, ending on whether the absent person is still the same, so the subject is the erosion of memory and certainty alike, not material choice or consolation.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-025", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH7, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["our harsher judgement of the driver who kills exposes a tension between blaming the will and blaming outcomes", "drunk drivers who kill should be punished less harshly than they are", "luck has no legitimate place in how we assign blame", "the two drivers are in every morally relevant respect different"], answer: 0, explanation: "The author presses the puzzle that identical choices draw unequal blame because of luck, leaving us either with an irrational practice or with blame that was never purely about the will, a tension rather than a verdict for leniency.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-026", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-vh7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH7, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's use of two drivers who are \"equally drunk and equally careless\" serves to...", format: "single_best", options: ["show that drunk driving is the real moral problem at issue", "hold the will fixed so the difference in blame can be traced to luck alone", "prove that the unlucky driver must have chosen more recklessly", "argue that both drivers are equally innocent of wrongdoing"], answer: 1, explanation: "By making the choices identical, the example isolates outcome luck as the sole variable, so any difference in blame must rest on something neither driver controlled.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-027", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH7, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing sentence implies that the genuinely \"uncomfortable thought\" is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the lucky driver is secretly guiltier than he appears", "the unlucky driver deserves no blame at all for the death", "luck should be formally written into the criminal law", "we may lack a principled justification for blaming the lucky driver as lightly as we do"], answer: 3, explanation: "The author specifies the discomfort: not that we should blame the killer less, but that we cannot give a principled reason why the merely lucky driver should be blamed less than we instinctively do.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-028", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-vh7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH7, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, \"fastening on outcomes\" most nearly means...", format: "single_best", options: ["repairing the damage that bad outcomes cause", "attaching judgement to results rather than to the choices that were made", "predicting outcomes before they actually occur", "ignoring outcomes in favour of intentions"], answer: 1, explanation: "To fasten on outcomes is for blame to fix itself to what resulted, which luck decides, instead of to the equally careless will the two drivers shared.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-029", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-vh8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH8, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Mrs Carrow is best understood as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a snob who is openly hostile to her northern guest", "a warm woman genuinely devoted to the young man's comfort", "a clumsy host who means well but lacks social skill", "a hostess whose displays of kindness quietly assert her superiority over her guest"], answer: 3, explanation: "Each gracious act, the placed compliment, the slow repetition, the public remark, diminishes the guest while preserving her appearance of warmth, so her kindness is a vehicle for condescension rather than hostility or mere clumsiness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-030", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH8, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That Mrs Carrow repeated his answers \"a little more slowly\" most strongly implies she...", format: "single_best", options: ["presented him to the table as a curiosity to be displayed rather than an equal in the talk", "could not hear his answers clearly and wished to confirm them", "admired his answers and wanted the others to learn from them", "was nervous and merely filling awkward silences"], answer: 0, explanation: "The simile of handing round something unfamiliar shows the slow repetition frames him as an exhibit for inspection, a polite belittling rather than admiration or nervousness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-031", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-vh8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH8, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's attitude toward Mrs Carrow is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["admiring of her considerable social accomplishment", "openly indignant on the young man's behalf", "coolly ironic, exposing her condescension through her own gracious gestures", "indifferent to the dynamics playing out at the table"], answer: 2, explanation: "The narration never denounces her; it lets her warmth convict her, an irony that reveals the cruelty inside the courtesy without overt indignation or approval.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-032", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH8, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly illustrates...", format: "single_best", options: ["the rudeness of guests who stop contributing to conversation", "the difficulty shy people face at formal dinners", "how social dominance can be exercised through the very forms of hospitality", "the kindness required to host an unfamiliar visitor well"], answer: 2, explanation: "The point is that hospitality's gestures can be turned into instruments of rank, the host putting the guest in his place precisely by appearing to put him at his ease.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-033", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH9, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["a poem is better seen as instructions for an experience that translation can reissue than as a fixed object", "a translated poem is always a wholly different and inferior work", "the sounds of the original language are irrelevant to a poem's meaning", "no two readings of any poem can ever be the same"], answer: 0, explanation: "The author resists the no-translation argument by reconceiving the poem as a set of instructions a translation can re-realise in new materials, captured in the statue recast as bronze.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-034", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-vh9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH9, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author objects that the no-translation argument \"proves too much\" because...", format: "single_best", options: ["it rests on evidence drawn from only a few poor translations", "the same reasoning would deny that even one reader could reread the original and meet the same poem", "it assumes translators lack any skill in the target language", "it ignores how much money translation actually requires"], answer: 1, explanation: "If meaning were inseparable from every particular of the first encounter, then a second reading in a different silence would also be a different poem, an absurd consequence that discredits the premise.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-035", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH9, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of the statue recast as bronze is offered to suggest that a good translation...", format: "single_best", options: ["has no real relation to the artist's original intention", "is inevitably cruder than the marble it sets out to imitate", "should preserve the exact words of the source above all", "aims to reproduce the work's effect in a new medium rather than to duplicate its original substance"], answer: 3, explanation: "Recasting, not copying, frames translation as carrying the work's function into new materials and asking whether the effect survives, not as duplicating the original stuff.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-036", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-vh9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH9, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "As used here, \"reissues\" most nearly means...", format: "single_best", options: ["repeats word for word without any change", "puts forth again in a new form so as to produce the same experience", "corrects the errors of an earlier version", "withdraws and replaces a flawed edition"], answer: 1, explanation: "The translation reissues the instructions in new materials, putting them forth afresh to yield the same experience, not a literal repetition or a mere correction.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-037", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-vh10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH10, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The \"pressure\" the speaker hears in the attic chiefly figures...", format: "single_best", options: ["the financial burden of the mortgage he owes", "a literal haunting by the previous owner's ghost", "the structural strain of an aging building", "the moral weight of benefiting from another's dispossession"], answer: 3, explanation: "The speaker says not ghost exactly and likens it to a debt you did not make, so the pressure is the conscience of one who profits from another's forced loss, not a haunting, decay, or mortgage.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-038", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH10, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The closing couplet implies that the speaker's deepest disquiet is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["he will enjoy what was taken from another while bearing almost no cost for it", "the legal title to the house may not be valid after all", "he paid far too high a price for the property", "the previous owner may one day return to claim it"], answer: 0, explanation: "The line that the undoing is how little he will pay names the true trouble: the gain is secure and cheap to him precisely because the cost fell on the one forced to sign and leave.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-039", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-vh10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH10, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The speaker's attitude across the poem is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["frightened of a genuine supernatural threat", "defiant and untroubled by the property's history", "uneasy and self-implicating despite his clear legal right", "resentful toward the lawyer who reassured him"], answer: 2, explanation: "He accepts that the house is lawfully his yet keeps turning the moral question back on himself, an unease that implicates him rather than defiance, fear of ghosts, or resentment.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-040", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH10, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem chiefly examines...", format: "single_best", options: ["the fear of living in an old and possibly haunted house", "the unreliability of property law in protecting buyers", "the gap between legal entitlement and moral comfort when one profits from another's loss", "the financial sacrifices required to own a home"], answer: 2, explanation: "The clean deeds set against the speaker's persistent disquiet dramatise that being entitled is not the same as being easy in conscience, the poem's central concern.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-041", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-vh11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH11, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage most strongly suggests that Agnes is...", format: "single_best", options: ["a person whose generosity proved real even though the debt that prompted it was imagined", "a fool who wasted thirty years on people who exploited her", "a liar who invented the Pooles' kindness to excuse herself", "a bitter woman seeking repayment for old wrongs"], answer: 0, explanation: "Her remembered debt was false, yet the kindnesses she gave were genuine and freely chosen, and she does not regret them, which marks authentic generosity rather than folly, deceit, or bitterness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-042", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH11, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That Agnes \"did not want the years back\" most strongly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["she has decided to demand compensation from the Poole family", "she judges the goodness she gave to be worth keeping regardless of the false belief that occasioned it", "she regrets every kindness she ever performed for the Pooles", "she still believes that the Pooles were genuinely kind to her"], answer: 1, explanation: "Knowing the debt was imaginary, she still values the years of care, implying the worth of her conduct does not depend on the mistaken motive that first set it going.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-043", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-vh11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH11, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The tone of the passage is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["cold and resigned", "angry and disillusioned", "comic and mocking", "reflective and quietly redemptive"], answer: 3, explanation: "The discovery of the error gives way not to bitterness but to a calm acceptance that the kindness still counted, a reflective tone that finds something redeemed rather than lost.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-044", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH11, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly explores...", format: "single_best", options: ["the danger of trusting one's own memory over written records", "how the value of what we do for others can outlast the truth of the reasons we believed we had", "the cruelty of families who exploit a young lodger", "the importance of keeping accurate accounts of debts"], answer: 1, explanation: "The false debt set against the real, freely given care raises whether goodness done for a mistaken reason still has worth, and Agnes's contentment answers yes, which is the passage's concern.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-045", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH12, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the layman should learn enough to weigh the arguments for himself", "laymen should always trust the more famous of two disagreeing experts", "expert disagreement proves that no expert can really be trusted", "suspending judgement between disagreeing experts is itself a judgement the layman is not equipped to make"], answer: 3, explanation: "The author contends that calling the dispute a tie is a substantive verdict of equal support, one the layman cannot warrant, so the recommended humility conceals a judgement rather than withholding one.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-046", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-vh12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH12, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that the layman \"cannot weigh the arguments, by hypothesis\" supports the conclusion that...", format: "single_best", options: ["his declaration of a tie cannot be a competent assessment, since judging equality needs the very skill he lacks", "experts ought to explain their reasoning far more simply", "the layman should defer to whichever expert is older", "the two experts cannot really be of equal standing"], answer: 0, explanation: "If being a layman just is being unable to weigh the arguments, then judging them equally weighty is beyond him too, so suspension is not a neutral refuge but an unearned verdict.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-047", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH12, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage implies that the \"honest position\" requires the layman to...", format: "single_best", options: ["treat both experts as exactly equally likely to be right", "abandon the question as one that cannot be answered", "accept that he must defer and then seek recognisable signs of which expert to trust", "become an expert himself before forming any view"], answer: 2, explanation: "The author says the harder, honest course is to admit deference and confront which marks of trustworthiness a non-expert can recognise, not to feign a tie or to acquire expertise.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-048", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-vh12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH12, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, \"smuggling one in\" most nearly means...", format: "single_best", options: ["borrowing an argument from another thinker", "openly defending a controversial opinion", "covertly introducing a judgement while appearing to make none", "postponing a decision to a later time"], answer: 2, explanation: "The phrase accuses the layman of slipping in a verdict, that the case is a tie, disguised as the modest act of withholding judgement.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-049", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-vh13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH13, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "Calling the field guide the place \"where the living go to be embalmed\" chiefly suggests that...", format: "single_best", options: ["naming and classifying can deaden the living thing they capture", "field guides contain factual errors about birds", "the birds described in the guide are already dead", "the speaker dislikes carrying a heavy book"], answer: 0, explanation: "Embalming a living thing figures how fixing the bird under a name preserves it only as a specimen, draining the vitality the unnamed song still has.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-050", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH13, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The speaker implies that the morning \"stays a wonder\" precisely because...", format: "single_best", options: ["it is too early in the day to see anything clearly", "it has not been reduced to a familiar category by being named", "the field guide does not happen to describe mornings", "the unnamed bird has at last been identified"], answer: 1, explanation: "Having no word for it keeps the morning from becoming a page, so its wonder survives by escaping the classification that would make it ordinary.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-051", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-vh13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH13, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The tone of the poem is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["mournful about the limits of human knowledge", "frustrated at the speaker's own ignorance", "scornful of birds and birdwatchers alike", "quietly celebratory of what eludes naming"], answer: 3, explanation: "The speaker welcomes not knowing the name and finds the unnamed song and morning richer for it, a celebratory rather than frustrated or mournful stance.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-052", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH14, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["we are never genuinely free to make any choices at all", "the freedom we value flows from our character rather than from a will unconditioned by it", "people frequently act against their own settled characters", "moral freedom requires the real ability to do evil"], answer: 1, explanation: "The author reframes prized freedom as issuing from who we are, showing that the most apparently open choices are the ones our settled character most fully determines.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-053", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-vh14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH14, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The example of possibly betraying a friend is used to show that...", format: "single_best", options: ["free choices are confined to trivial matters", "betrayal is the most common test of any friendship", "everyone is secretly capable of betraying a friend", "the sense of an open alternative is strongest where our character would in fact prevent the act"], answer: 3, explanation: "We feel freest to betray exactly where our character ensures we would not, so the felt openness coincides with, rather than escapes, the conditioning of the will.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-054", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH14, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing image of \"a wall I have become\" most strongly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["what we experience as open possibility is often the firm settledness of our own character", "our choices are imposed on us by external barriers", "people cannot change their characters over a lifetime", "freedom and character are wholly unrelated to each other"], answer: 0, explanation: "The door that seems open is reinterpreted as a wall, the speaker's own formed nature, suggesting felt possibility is really the solidity of who one has become, not an outside constraint.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-055", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-vh14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH14, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "As used here, \"unconditioned\" most nearly describes a will that is...", format: "single_best", options: ["not yet trained or disciplined", "unhealthy through a lack of exercise", "not shaped or determined by the agent's own character", "free of any legal restriction"], answer: 2, explanation: "The unconditioned will is one acting independently of the agent's character, the very thing the passage denies we possess or should prize.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-056", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-vh15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH15, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Mr Avery is best understood as a man who...", format: "single_best", options: ["is honestly mistaken about the true level of the boy's talent", "genuinely sacrifices his own standing to protect a fragile student", "disguises his envy of the boy's gift as concern for the boy's character", "openly resents the boy and makes no secret of it"], answer: 2, explanation: "His low marks, dampening speeches and watching for a shadow betray a wish to diminish the boy, rationalised as protection, and the closing memory of his own failure supplies the envy beneath the kindness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-057", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH15, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The final sentence about the \"door that failed to open\" most strongly implies that Mr Avery's behaviour is driven by...", format: "single_best", options: ["his own thwarted ambition, now turned against a boy who might succeed where he did not", "a sincere educational theory about the perils of early praise", "a long-standing grudge against the boy's family", "a duty imposed on him by the school's administration"], answer: 0, explanation: "The buried disappointment of his own youth, in the same school, links his treatment of the boy to a wound of his own, pointing to envy of another's open door rather than genuine pedagogy.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-058", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-vh15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH15, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's handling of Mr Avery is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["warmly sympathetic to his protective instincts", "quietly damning, exposing the self-deception behind his kindness", "neutral, withholding any judgement at all", "broadly comic and affectionate"], answer: 1, explanation: "By noting that he almost believed his own excuse and designed his words to cast a shadow, the narrator lays bare the cruelty under the care, a restrained condemnation rather than sympathy or neutrality.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-059", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH15, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly illustrates...", format: "single_best", options: ["the difficulty of marking creative work objectively", "the genuine risk that early praise poses to gifted children", "the unfairness of regional academic prizes", "how envy can clothe itself convincingly in the language of care and protection"], answer: 3, explanation: "The point is the disguise: Avery's resentment of the boy's promise presents itself, even to himself, as kindly concern, which is the situation the passage anatomises.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-060", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH16, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["statues are reliable historical records that ought to be preserved", "monuments quietly assert contestable claims about the past while appearing only to record it", "disputes over statues are really disputes about historical facts", "removing a monument always amounts to erasing the past"], answer: 1, explanation: "The author casts a monument as a proposal disguised as fact, so disputes concern which claims get to look natural, and both leaving and removing are endorsements or their withdrawal, not neutral recording.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-061", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-vh16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH16, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The detail that the general \"simply stands\" rather than arguing supports the claim that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the public has forgotten which war the statue commemorates", "equestrian statues are an outdated artistic form", "generals are unsuitable subjects for public memorials", "a monument's persuasive force lies in presenting a contestable judgement as settled fact"], answer: 3, explanation: "Standing in the calm of settled fact, where argument seems ill-mannered, is exactly how the monument advances its proposal most effectively, illustrating the disguise the author describes.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-062", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH16, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage implies that allowing a monument to remain standing is...", format: "single_best", options: ["an ongoing endorsement that the present renews simply by tolerating it", "a neutral act with no bearing on present values", "a purely practical decision about the use of public space", "a guarantee that the historical record stays accurate"], answer: 0, explanation: "The author states the standing is itself the claim and that letting the figure stand renews a particular endorsement daily, so tolerance is not neutrality but continued assent.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-063", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-vh16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH16, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, \"proposal\" most nearly means...", format: "single_best", options: ["an offer of marriage or partnership", "a formal plan submitted for official approval", "an implicit claim about how the past should be regarded", "a budget request for public funds"], answer: 2, explanation: "The monument's proposal is its tacit assertion about the worth of what it commemorates, a claim about how we should regard the past, not a plan, an offer, or a budget.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-064", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-vh17", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH17, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The simile of the coin that \"outlasts the thing it cost\" chiefly conveys that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the speaker regrets the money spent on photographs", "the picture was an expensive object to produce", "the photograph endures while the living moment it stood for has been lost", "laughter can be exchanged for lasting keepsakes"], answer: 2, explanation: "As a coin survives the purchase it once made, the photo persists after the moment it recorded is gone, keeping the proof while the meaning, the living laughter, has slipped away.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-065", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh17", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH17, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The phrase \"doing duty for all the times I failed to lift a lens\" most strongly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the single image is burdened with standing in for many unrecorded moments", "the speaker took a great many photographs of the person", "the camera repeatedly failed at the crucial moment", "the person disliked being photographed while laughing"], answer: 0, explanation: "One picture must substitute for all the laughter the speaker never captured, so the surviving image bears the weight of everything that went unrecorded.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-066", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-vh17", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH17, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The tone of the poem is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["bitter and accusatory", "wistful and faintly self-reproachful", "detached and analytical", "hopeful and consoled"], answer: 1, explanation: "The speaker mourns the lost sound and gently blames the failure to lift a lens, mixing longing with quiet self-reproach rather than bitterness, detachment, or consolation.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-067", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-vh18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH18, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly argues that...", format: "single_best", options: ["every generation faces exactly the same burdens as the last", "earlier generations really did enjoy safer and more honest communities", "nostalgia is a useful and reliable guide to how society has changed", "belief in a lost golden age confuses the carefree view of childhood with a genuine decline of the world"], answer: 3, explanation: "The author explains the recurring golden age as a misreading: the remembered ease is the irresponsibility of childhood, not a better world, so the sense of decline tracks growing up rather than real change.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-068", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-vh18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH18, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The observation that the golden age is dated \"with suspicious regularity\" to the speaker's own childhood works to...", format: "single_best", options: ["prove that childhoods have grown worse over the centuries", "expose the bias that undermines the memory's claim to record real decline", "show that different generations agree about when things were best", "establish that memories of childhood are usually inaccurate in detail"], answer: 1, explanation: "That everyone's golden age conveniently coincides with their own childhood reveals the judgement as an artefact of the observer's position rather than evidence about the world, which is the author's point.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-069", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-vh18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH18, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage implies that what the nostalgic person actually grieves is...", format: "single_best", options: ["the specific hardships that are unique to modern life", "the disappearance of communities that genuinely existed", "the failure of the present generation to honour the past", "the loss of a child's freedom from responsibility, misnamed as a decline of the world"], answer: 3, explanation: "The closing lines say the grief is, under another name, for the loss of being young, the lightening of a child's load mistaken for the strengthening of the times.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-vh-070", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-vh18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: VH18, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, \"seen from below\" most nearly means...", format: "single_best", options: ["viewed from the vantage of a child not yet charged with adult cares", "remembered as a time of poverty and hardship", "observed from a position of social inferiority", "judged unfairly by later and harsher standards"], answer: 0, explanation: "Seen from below describes the child's-eye view, beneath the responsibilities later handed over, which is why the past looks lighter and easier than the present.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-017", genre: "graphic", skill: "main_idea", aiImagePending: true, stimulusId: "gs1-grai1", stimulus: { kind: "image", content: "assets/s1/welfare-net.png", alt: "Four officials in business suits each grip one corner of a large net labelled WELFARE and stride outward, stretching it until a wide hole opens in the centre, through which a small ordinary person drops toward the ground. The officials face away from the centre with calm, composed expressions.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "The cartoon most strongly suggests that the welfare safety net is...", format: "single_best", options: ["no longer needed by the person who is falling", "too small ever to have caught anyone in the first place", "being pulled apart by the very people meant to maintain it, so it fails those who depend on it", "being carefully repaired by the four officials"], answer: 2, explanation: "Each official pulls a corner outward, opening the hole the small figure falls through, so the net keeps its name while being stretched to uselessness by the very people charged with holding it.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-018", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", aiImagePending: true, stimulusId: "gs1-grai1", stimulus: { kind: "image", content: "assets/s1/welfare-net.png", alt: "Four officials in business suits each grip one corner of a large net labelled WELFARE and stride outward, stretching it until a wide hole opens in the centre, through which a small ordinary person drops toward the ground. The officials face away from the centre with calm, composed expressions.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "The officials' calm, unhurried manner as the figure falls most strongly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the officials are straining their hardest to hold the net together", "the officials have not yet noticed that anyone is falling", "the dismantling of the net is deliberate and untroubling to them, not an accident they regret", "the falling figure is in no real danger"], answer: 2, explanation: "They stride outward holding the net while wearing composed faces, so the collapse reads as something they are doing on purpose and are unbothered by, rather than a lapse they are fighting to prevent.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-019", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", aiImagePending: true, stimulusId: "gs1-grai2", stimulus: { kind: "image", content: "assets/s1/engagement-screens.png", alt: "A single viewer sits in a chair between two glowing screens that face them from the left and right, each screen showing an opposite slogan. Cables run from both screens to one large machine behind the viewer labelled ENGAGEMENT. The viewer leans forward, transfixed, with a rapt, delighted expression.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "That both opposing screens are wired to a single machine labelled ENGAGEMENT most strongly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the apparent opposition is driven by one shared motive, capturing the viewer's attention", "one of the two screens must be telling the truth", "the viewer is choosing what each screen displays", "the machine has broken and is showing content at random"], answer: 0, explanation: "If both sides are fed by a single engine, the clash is less a genuine disagreement than two outputs of the same attention-seeking source, so the opposition serves one shared motive.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-020", genre: "graphic", skill: "main_idea", aiImagePending: true, stimulusId: "gs1-grai2", stimulus: { kind: "image", content: "assets/s1/engagement-screens.png", alt: "A single viewer sits in a chair between two glowing screens that face them from the left and right, each screen showing an opposite slogan. Cables run from both screens to one large machine behind the viewer labelled ENGAGEMENT. The viewer leans forward, transfixed, with a rapt, delighted expression.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "The cartoon's central point is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["people ought to follow more than one news source", "what looks like two opposing sides can be manufactured by a single source that profits from attention", "screens are gradually replacing human conversation", "the viewer holds unusually strong political opinions"], answer: 1, explanation: "Two opposed feeds running from one ENGAGEMENT machine make the clash a product of a single attention-seeking source, which is the overall message rather than a point about screen time or the viewer's opinions.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-021", genre: "graphic", skill: "tone", aiImagePending: true, stimulusId: "gs1-grai3", stimulus: { kind: "image", content: "assets/s1/moving-finish-line.png", alt: "An exhausted runner wearing a race bib labelled APPLICANT strains forward toward a finish-line tape, face contorted with effort and streaked with sweat. Just ahead, a composed official in a suit holding a clipboard labelled REQUIREMENTS walks calmly onward, carrying the finish-line tape further away so it can never be reached.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "The attitude the cartoon takes toward the way the standard is set is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["hopeful that the runner will cross the line soon", "neutral and merely descriptive", "admiring of the official's careful diligence", "critical, mocking a target that is carried out of reach as it is approached"], answer: 3, explanation: "Carrying the finish line away as the runner strains toward it ridicules a standard that shifts so it can never be met, which is pointed mockery rather than neutral description or admiration.", difficulty: "medium", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-022", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", aiImagePending: true, stimulusId: "gs1-grai3", stimulus: { kind: "image", content: "assets/s1/moving-finish-line.png", alt: "An exhausted runner wearing a race bib labelled APPLICANT strains forward toward a finish-line tape, face contorted with effort and streaked with sweat. Just ahead, a composed official in a suit holding a clipboard labelled REQUIREMENTS walks calmly onward, carrying the finish-line tape further away so it can never be reached.", attribution: "Original cartoon" }, stem: "The contrast between the straining runner and the official calmly carrying the tape onward most strongly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the applicant has simply not trained hard enough for the race", "the applicant's failure to finish reflects the moving standard, not any lack of effort", "the official is trying to help the applicant win", "the finish line is fixed and has been fairly placed"], answer: 1, explanation: "The runner's visible effort set against the official quietly relocating the line places the cause of failure on the shifting requirement rather than on the applicant, whose exertion is real.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-001", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The central claim of the passage is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["understanding the causes of an action is the first step toward forgiving it", "a causal explanation of an action and the assignment of responsibility for it are independent, so neither settles the other", "cruelty should be neither explained nor excused, since attempting either weakens moral judgement", "those who search for the causes of wrongdoing are morally more serious than those who refuse to"], answer: 1, explanation: "The thesis is that explanation and exculpation are separate questions that do not compete: we may understand everything and forgive nothing. The forgiving-follows-from-understanding option is the very error the author refutes, since he calls forgiveness a further act, not a conclusion forced upon us. The neither-explain-nor-excuse option recommends the refusal to inquire that he attacks, not his own position. The morally-more-serious option tempts because he does mock ignorance posing as vigilance, yet he charges both camps with the identical mistake and ranks neither above the other.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-002", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The comparison with the engineer who 'skimped on the steel' is used to show that...", format: "single_best", options: ["responsibility can survive a complete account of how a failure was caused", "some failures are too technical to be judged in moral terms", "most wrongdoing results from negligence rather than deliberate malice", "physical events, unlike human choices, can be explained all the way down"], answer: 0, explanation: "We can say exactly why the bridge fell, the skimped steel, and still hold the engineer to blame; the analogy shows full explanation and responsibility are compatible, which is the point about the liar. The too-technical option reverses that force, since the example exists precisely to deliver a moral verdict. The negligence option generalises about the causes of wrongdoing, a frequency claim the analogy never makes, with 'skimped' as the bait. The physical-versus-human option sounds sophisticated but inverts the passage, which draws a parallel between bridge and lie rather than a contrast.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-003", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST1, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'ignorance were a form of moral vigilance' characterises people who...", format: "single_best", options: ["fear that examining the causes of cruelty will tempt us to pardon it, and so refuse to examine them", "hold that genuine moral alertness depends on understanding how cruelty arises", "are too poorly informed to recognise cruelty when they meet it", "believe that moral questions can never be settled either way"], answer: 0, explanation: "These are the people who refuse to look for causes because understanding might end by pardoning, so they treat not-knowing as a way of guarding morality; the phrase is ironic. The moral-alertness option reverses it, stating the opposing camp's premise that knowledge aids judgement, and 'vigilance' pairing with knowledge is the trap. The poorly-informed option misreads 'ignorance' as cluelessness rather than a deliberate refusal to inquire, though these people do recognise the cruelty. The never-settled option imports a moral scepticism the passage does not raise.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-004", genre: "testing", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-test2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The detail that Margaret had the coffin turned to face the garden chiefly reveals that she...", format: "single_best", options: ["wanted the funeral to appear correct in the eyes of the neighbours", "felt a grief she expressed through small, private acts of care rather than open display", "wished to be seen taking charge of every arrangement", "had so practical and organising a temperament that little room was left for feeling"], answer: 1, explanation: "Turning the coffin toward the garden their father loved is a private tenderness she checks twice and that the neighbours never even notice, which the undertaker reads as grief leaving by the narrowest of doors. The appear-correct option makes it a performance, but the gesture is unwitnessed, the opposite of for-show. The seen-taking-charge option needs an audience the moment lacks, since it is the brother who is watched and consoled. The practical-temperament option simply restates the neighbours' verdict of cold and capable, the misreading the passage is built to overturn, which is why it is the strongest distractor: her capability hides feeling rather than crowding it out.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-005", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's saying the brother 'wept handsomely into a borrowed handkerchief' most strongly implies that his grief was...", format: "single_best", options: ["deeper than Margaret's, but harder for others to see", "sincere, though more violent than his sister's", "at least partly a performance, more shown than felt", "wholly feigned for the benefit of the neighbours"], answer: 2, explanation: "'Handsomely' praises the style of the weeping, a thing done well and attractively, 'borrowed' makes even the prop improvised and theatrical, and he is much consoled; set against Margaret's hidden grief this reads as display. The deeper-but-hidden option reverses the passage, since it is her grief that is hard to see. The sincere-but-violent option takes the tears at face value and ignores the loaded diction. The wholly-feigned option goes too far, overstating what the words license, which is grief mixed with performance rather than pure fraud, and the line between this option and the keyed one is the test.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-006", genre: "testing", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-test2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST2, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's attitude toward the neighbours' judgement of Margaret is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["quietly corrective", "openly indignant", "amused and dismissive", "neutral and merely reportorial"], answer: 0, explanation: "The narrator never argues with the neighbours; instead the undertaker's detail is allowed to overturn their verdict, a gentle correction rather than a protest. The openly-indignant option overstates the temperature, since there is sympathy but no raised voice. The amused-and-dismissive option mistakes the tender treatment of Margaret for mockery. The neutral option is the subtle trap: the prose is restrained, but restraint is not neutrality, and a truly reportorial narrator would not editorialise about grief leaving by the narrowest of doors or arrange the detail so as to take her side.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-007", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem is chiefly concerned with...", format: "single_best", options: ["the loneliness that accompanies a public life", "the way courting approval can hollow out the very words that win it", "the speaker's gratitude for a generous and appreciative audience", "the difficulty of composing an original speech"], answer: 1, explanation: "Praise carried like borrowed plate, the acknowledged bargain, and the pleasing sentence repeated until the clapping was the speech and none still heard, together trace approval draining meaning from the words. The loneliness option tempts through 'none, not least himself, still heard,' but the loss is of meaning, not company. The gratitude option inverts the tone, since the praise is suspect and he is afraid to look too closely. The originality option names a labour the poem never raises; the problem is corrupting repetition, not the strain of invention.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-008", genre: "testing", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-test3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The image of carrying praise 'like borrowed plate, / afraid to look too closely at the shine' suggests that the praise is...", format: "single_best", options: ["valuable, but a burden to carry from place to place", "impressive on its surface, yet not truly his and unable to bear scrutiny", "fragile, and easily broken in the handling", "stolen from someone who deserved it more"], answer: 1, explanation: "'Borrowed' marks it as not his own, 'plate' supplies show and surface shine, and 'afraid to look too closely' tells us it will not survive inspection: impressive but unowned and unsound. The burden option reads 'carry' too literally and drops both 'borrowed' and the fear of looking. The fragile option imports a breakability the lines never raise; the stress is on borrowedness and surface. The stolen option slides 'borrowed' into theft and adds a guilt the poem does not assert, since borrowing means the thing is not his and must be returned, not that he took it.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-009", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST3, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The final image, 'the clapping was the speech, / and none, not least himself, still heard,' most strongly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["his audiences eventually stopped coming to listen", "he had over the years grown deaf to criticism", "the ritual of approval had entirely replaced anything worth hearing", "his later speeches were delivered more quietly and were harder to hear"], answer: 2, explanation: "When the clapping has become the speech, the response has swallowed the substance, and none still heard means there is no longer anything to hear, the speaker included. The empty-hall reading literalises 'none heard,' yet they are still clapping, so the audience is present and what is lost is meaning. The deaf-to-criticism reading imports objections the poem never mentions. The quieter-speeches reading mistakes a metaphor about emptiness for a remark about volume.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-010", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main contention is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["to tolerate a practice is a disguised way of endorsing it", "toleration presupposes disapproval, so it is the opposite of endorsement, though it can decay into indifference", "a state ought to forbid only those practices of which the majority disapproves", "indifference toward a disliked practice is preferable to forbidding it"], answer: 1, explanation: "Both of the author's moves are needed: toleration is disapproval held in check, hence the opposite of endorsement, and it can decay by degrees into indifference. The endorsement option is exactly the complaint the author says mistakes the nature of toleration. The majority option is a policy rule the passage never offers. The preferring-indifference option inverts the author's evaluation, since he names that slide the genuine danger; it tempts because he does separate toleration from prohibition, but he warns against indifference rather than recommending it.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-011", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that 'there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves' supports the idea that...", format: "single_best", options: ["approval and toleration are simply two names for one attitude", "toleration is meaningful only when its object is something one objects to", "people seldom in fact approve of the practices they permit", "a tolerant person must stay neutral about whatever they allow"], answer: 1, explanation: "If approval leaves nothing to tolerate, toleration must by definition apply to the disapproved, since it needs a standing objection to restrain. The one-attitude option is the reverse, for the line drives a wedge between approval and toleration. The seldom-approve option is an empirical frequency the conceptual point does not make. The neutrality option is the central trap the passage rejects: the tolerant person is not neutral but disapproving and self-restrained, and treating toleration as neutrality is the very decay the author warns of.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-012", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST4, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "According to the passage, toleration 'decays by degrees into... indifference' when...", format: "single_best", options: ["a society comes to approve of the practice it once merely permitted", "the disapproval that toleration restrains gradually fades, leaving only the permission", "the state at last forbids the practice it had allowed", "people become steadily more vocal in condemning the practice"], answer: 1, explanation: "Toleration is disapproval held in check; if the disapproval itself fades, the restraint acts on nothing and only the habit of permitting remains, the society having forgotten it dislikes the thing at all. The closest wrong answer is coming to approve of the practice, but the passage describes disapproval thinning into not-caring, not flipping into positive endorsement, a different end-state. Prohibition is the opposite of the described drift. Growing condemnation would strengthen the disapproval, moving away from indifference rather than toward it.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-013", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The central claim of the passage is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["people ought not to exercise their rights in ways that others judge to be wrong", "having a right to do a thing is distinct from its being right to do it, and confusing the two corrupts how we speak of liberty", "most exercises of a right turn out, on inspection, to be harmless", "a right is only worth defending when the action it protects is a good one"], answer: 1, explanation: "The passage separates the protected sphere of a right from the merit of the act done within it, and blames the slide between them for coarsening talk of liberty. The first option recommends a standard of conduct the passage does not set, since it concerns what we may say of an act, not what people should choose. The harmless option is the evasion the author criticises, not his thesis. The last option inverts him, since his point is that a right protects even the act we judge bad.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-014", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'approval wearing its costume' is used to argue that a liberty limited to approved choices would be...", format: "single_best", options: ["not genuine liberty at all, but mere approval in disguise", "a liberty that depends on winning the agreement of others", "a more civilised form of freedom than unlimited liberty", "concerned chiefly with outward appearances and manners"], answer: 0, explanation: "If you may do only what others approve, nothing is protected that approval would not already allow, so the liberty is approval under another name. The dependence option merely restates the condition the metaphor exposes rather than naming what is wrong with it. The civilised option praises what the author rejects, and the appearances option reads costume literally, missing the disguise.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-015", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In saying the slide 'runs in both directions' and that both camps 'evade the same difficulty', the author means that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the two camps secretly hold the same opinion about the act", "both refuse to accept that a right must protect even an act they judge mistaken", "one camp argues more honestly than the other", "the real question is always whether the act causes harm"], answer: 1, explanation: "Both the right-deniers and the harmless-callers dodge the hard truth that a right binds us even where we think its use wrong, and that shared evasion is the difficulty. The same-opinion option mistakes a shared evasion for a shared view of the act. Ranking one camp as more honest is not claimed; he treats them as symmetrical. The harm option is itself one of the evasions, not his position.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-016", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, to 'coarsen the way we speak of liberty' most nearly means to...", format: "single_best", options: ["make public speech ruder and more aggressive", "reduce how often liberty is discussed at all", "make our discussion of liberty cruder by collapsing a distinction it needs", "make liberty itself harsher in its effects"], answer: 2, explanation: "The coarsening is of how we reason about liberty, specifically the loss of the right-versus-good distinction. The rudeness option takes coarsen as bad manners rather than crude thinking. The frequency option swaps quality for quantity. The last option misplaces the coarsening onto liberty itself rather than onto our talk of it.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-017", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST5, attribution: "Original passage" }, addedInfo: "Consider, however, the case of a right exercised so as to destroy the conditions on which the same right depends for everyone else: the speaker, say, whose whole purpose is to have dissenting speakers silenced. Here the difficulty sharpens, for to protect the exercise is to license the dismantling of the protection itself. Some conclude that such an exercise forfeits its claim to be protected; others, that to make the protection conditional on its being used in approved ways is precisely the move the argument was meant to forbid.", stem: "The added case of the speaker who wants dissenters silenced is introduced in order to...", format: "single_best", options: ["refute the distinction the passage has so far defended", "give a plain example of an act that is merely harmful to others", "present a hard case that sharpens, rather than dissolves, the earlier distinction", "prove that rights should never be subject to any limit"], answer: 2, explanation: "The case is offered as one where the difficulty sharpens, a genuine pressure on the distinction rather than its refutation or its proof. The refute option overstates, since the passage frames it as hard, not as overturning the thesis. The merely-harmful option misses what is special, that the act attacks the right itself. The never-limit option takes a side the passage explicitly leaves open.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-018", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The view that such an exercise 'forfeits its claim to be protected' most resembles which move described earlier in the passage?", format: "single_best", options: ["calling an act harmless in order to defend it", "withdrawing a right because of the character of the act, now applied under greater pressure", "the author's own thesis about the binding force of rights", "the claim that liberty requires the approval of others"], answer: 1, explanation: "Forfeiture withdraws protection on account of how the right is used, the same structure as denying a right because the deed is wrong, here pushed by a harder case. The harmless option is the opposite evasion. It cannot be the author's thesis, which resists conditioning rights on approved use. The approval option names a different idea, about the source of liberty rather than its forfeiture.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-019", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST5, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Taking the passage as a whole, including the added case, the author's considered position is best described as holding that...", format: "single_best", options: ["rights should be revoked whenever they are exercised so as to cause harm", "the self-undermining case shows that the very idea of rights is incoherent", "rights protect even mistaken or harmful exercises, while the self-undermining case is left standing as a genuine difficulty", "the limits of liberty should be fixed by what the community approves"], answer: 2, explanation: "Throughout, the author defends protection for acts judged wrong, and the closing case is presented as an unresolved hard problem, not a settled exception. The revoke-on-harm option adopts an evasion he criticises. The incoherence option overreads a difficulty as a collapse. The community-approval option is the disguised liberty he rejects.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-020", genre: "testing", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-test6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST6, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "As initially presented in the first paragraph, Henshaw is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a man whose charity is wholly fraudulent", "a modest philanthropist indifferent to recognition", "a man whose giving is real in its effects but carefully arranged to be seen", "a man who gives only when it brings him direct financial return"], answer: 2, explanation: "He genuinely funds the roof and the scholarship, yet times and labels his giving for visibility, so the effects are real and the staging deliberate. The fraudulent option ignores that the gifts are real. The modest option contradicts the brass plate and the chosen moments. The direct-return option overstates, since seeking repute is not the same as direct profit, a gap the second paragraph widens.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-021", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST6, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The schoolmaster's remark that 'virtue, advertised, pays a better rate of interest than virtue concealed' implies that he regards Henshaw's generosity as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a calculated investment in his own reputation rather than disinterested kindness", "financially reckless and likely to ruin him", "genuinely selfless and wrongly doubted by others", "secretly resented by the townspeople who benefit"], answer: 0, explanation: "The banking metaphor casts the giving as spending that buys a return in standing, the opposite of disinterest. The reckless option misreads pays as losing money. The selfless option is the schoolmaster's contrary, not his view. The resented option introduces the town's feelings, which the remark does not touch.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-022", genre: "testing", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-test6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST6, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In the first paragraph, the narrator's stance toward the competing verdicts of the vicar and the schoolmaster is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["firmly on the side of the vicar", "poised and withholding, setting out both without yet endorsing either", "openly contemptuous of Henshaw", "indifferent to which verdict is correct"], answer: 1, explanation: "The narrator reports the pillar and the cynic side by side, reserving judgement until the second paragraph reopens the question. The vicar option picks a side the text has not taken. The contempt option imports a hostility absent from the careful framing. The indifferent option mistakes withholding for not caring, but the next paragraph shows the narrator does care.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-023", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST6, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The statement that 'self-interest is an economical hypothesis, but it is not always the most economical' makes the point that...", format: "single_best", options: ["kindness is always a cheaper explanation than selfishness", "Henshaw managed his money poorly", "explaining a deed by self-interest can require more strained assumptions than explaining it by kindness", "the simplest explanation of any action is always the correct one"], answer: 2, explanation: "Economical here means requiring fewer forced assumptions, and sometimes the selfish reading must strain so hard that kindness is the simpler fit. The always-cheaper option overgeneralises in the other direction. The money option literalises economical. The simplest-is-correct option states a rule the sentence is actually qualifying.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-024", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST6, attribution: "Original passage" }, addedInfo: "After Henshaw died it emerged that for thirty years he had paid the rent of a family in the next county whom no one in the parish had ever met, and had forbidden the agent who arranged it to record his name. The schoolmaster, told of this at the funeral, was silent for a time, and then said only that he supposed a man might wear one face for the town and keep another for himself, and that he had perhaps mistaken which was the disguise.", stem: "The disclosure of the secret thirty-year payment chiefly functions to...", format: "single_best", options: ["prove that Henshaw never cared about his reputation at all", "supply the disinterested motive the cynical reading could not account for, tipping the balance the second paragraph had left open", "show that the schoolmaster was simply envious of Henshaw", "confirm that all of Henshaw's giving had been performed for show"], answer: 1, explanation: "A gift deliberately kept nameless cannot be reputation-buying, so it supplies exactly the unselfish motive the suspicion could not explain, settling the doubt toward kindness. The never-cared option overstates, since his public giving still courted notice. The envy option is not established by the secret gift. The all-for-show option is contradicted by the disclosure itself.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-025", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST6, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The schoolmaster's closing reflection that he had 'perhaps mistaken which was the disguise' suggests that he now suspects that...", format: "single_best", options: ["Henshaw had deceived the whole parish about the size of his fortune", "the secret gift, too, was ultimately calculated", "the public, self-advertising face may have been the mask over a genuine private kindness, not the reverse", "no one can ever know the motives of another person"], answer: 2, explanation: "Wondering which face was the disguise reverses his earlier verdict, so the showy benefactor may be the act and the hidden giver the real man. The fortune option changes the subject to money. The still-calculated option ignores that the gift was concealed. The unknowable option is a general scepticism the remark does not reach, since it leans toward one particular new reading rather than throwing up its hands.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-026", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST6, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Read as a whole, the passage is best understood as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a demonstration that public charity is usually hypocrisy", "an argument that human motives can never be judged", "a caution against the reflexive cynicism that reads every visible virtue as self-interest, since suspicion can be the lazier explanation", "the story of a hypocrite who is finally exposed after his death"], answer: 2, explanation: "The movement is from easy suspicion to a fact that suspicion cannot absorb, warning that the cynical reading is not always the most economical. The usually-hypocrisy option draws the opposite moral. The never-judge option overstates into total scepticism. The exposed-hypocrite option gets the ending backwards, since death reveals kindness, not fraud.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-027", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST7, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The central claim of the passage is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["accident reports are usually inaccurate about what happened", "naming one factor as 'the cause' among many necessary conditions reflects our interests and our assignment of responsibility, not a bare fact about the event", "fires have too many causes to be explained at all", "the spark, not the oxygen, is the true cause of a fire"], answer: 1, explanation: "The passage argues that selecting the cause from a web of equally necessary conditions is a choice guided by where blame should fall. The inaccuracy option misses the point, since the report is not wrong but selective. The too-many option treats selection as impossibility. The spark option asserts the very privileging the passage calls a choice.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-028", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST7, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The treatment of oxygen as a 'mere condition' is used to show that...", format: "single_best", options: ["oxygen matters less to a fire than the spark does", "the line between cause and condition is one we impose, since the fire required both equally", "fires are physically too complex for anyone to understand", "official reports deliberately omit important facts"], answer: 1, explanation: "Oxygen is as necessary as the spark, so calling one cause and the other condition is our distinction, not the fire's. The matters-less option accepts the ranking the passage questions. The too-complex option overstates into unintelligibility. The deliberately option imputes a bad faith the passage does not allege here.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-029", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST7, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that 'the search for causes is already, half-secretly, a search for the responsible' means that...", format: "single_best", options: ["we tend to designate as the cause whatever condition someone could and should have changed", "looking for causes is a waste of effort", "blame has no place in an honest accident report", "the responsible party is always, in fact, the true cause"], answer: 0, explanation: "We pick out as the cause the alterable condition that locates responsibility, which is why causal inquiry doubles as blame-finding. The waste option does not follow. The no-place option is a recommendation the passage does not make. The always-true option collapses the very distinction between selection and fact that the passage draws.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-030", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST7, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the factory owner and the union each find the 'real cause' 'with perfect sincerity' most strongly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["one of the two must be lying about what happened", "people can honestly select different causes because each fixes on the condition that suits a prior view, without conscious dishonesty", "sincerity guarantees that a causal judgement is correct", "their disagreement is merely verbal and concerns nothing real"], answer: 1, explanation: "Sincerity together with opposite conclusions shows the selection is shaped by prior interest rather than deceit. The lying option contradicts perfect sincerity. The guarantee option confuses honesty with accuracy. The merely-verbal option goes too far, since each picks a genuinely necessary condition and the dispute tracks real questions of responsibility.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-031", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST7, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, 'the strand that points where they were already looking' refers to...", format: "single_best", options: ["the physically most powerful cause of the fire", "a literal thread found in the wreckage", "the necessary condition that happens to confirm the conclusion each party had already reached", "the condition that would be easiest to prove in court"], answer: 2, explanation: "The strand is one condition out of the web, chosen because it confirms a pre-existing view. The most-powerful option reintroduces a ranking the passage denies. The literal-thread option misreads the metaphor. The easiest-to-prove option swaps confirmation of a prior belief for evidential convenience, which is not what 'where they were already looking' means.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-032", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST8, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To the doctor's patients, calling him a 'plain man' chiefly means that he is...", format: "single_best", options: ["intellectually limited and behind the times", "unintimidating and free of jargon", "morally honest and without concealment", "physically unremarkable in appearance"], answer: 1, explanation: "For patients the word means unfrightening, a man who would not dress a verdict in Latin. The limited option is the colleagues' sense, not the patients'. The honest option is the wife's older sense. The appearance option is a meaning the passage never assigns.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-033", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST8, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That 'plain' means different things to the patients, the colleagues and the wife is used to show that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the doctor was misunderstood by nearly everyone", "plain speech inevitably causes confusion", "a single familiar-seeming word can carry sharply different judgements depending on who uses it", "only the wife understood the doctor correctly"], answer: 2, explanation: "The same word splits into unfrightening, limited and unconcealed, so one plain word holds three verdicts. The misunderstood option imports a complaint, since the doctor is content to let each meaning stand. The confusion option blames plain speech in general. The only-the-wife option overstates, since the patients' meaning is not wrong, only partial.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-034", genre: "testing", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-test8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST8, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In describing the doctor through 'a plain is open country with nothing to hide behind', the wife's sense of the word casts him as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a man of dull and featureless character", "a man without concealment or pretence, transparent in what he is", "a man of humble rural background", "a man with no defences against the judgements of others"], answer: 1, explanation: "Paired with her image of him sitting unpaid with the dying, the open plain figures a man with nothing hidden, honest through and through. The dull option takes plain as featureless, the patients' register, not hers. The rural option literalises the landscape. The defenceless option reads 'nothing to hide behind' as vulnerability rather than the absence of anything to conceal.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-035", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST8, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing idea that 'a word everyone thought they understood was the safest possible disguise' implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the doctor actively lied to people about his character", "common words are always clearer than rare ones", "a familiar word lets each person settle on a comfortable meaning and so overlook the rest of the man", "the doctor wished above all to be thought simple"], answer: 2, explanation: "Because each listener assumes the word is plain, none looks past their own version of it, so the word conceals by seeming transparent. The lied option overstates, since he conceals by letting others fill in the word, not by asserting falsehoods. The clearer option draws a general lexical moral the passage does not. The wished-to-be-simple option mistakes the effect of the disguise for a motive he is never given.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-036", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST9, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem is chiefly concerned with...", format: "single_best", options: ["the speaker's grief at the death of the woman who made the garden", "the way preserving something exactly can mean working against its own living nature", "the hard physical labour of maintaining a garden", "the speaker's wish to replace the garden with one of his own"], answer: 1, explanation: "Keeping the bed frozen at one year's plan sets the fixed shape against 'the life it wants', the poem's central tension. The grief option names an undertone but not the argument. The labour option literalises 'heavy'. The replace option contradicts the speaker's reluctant faithfulness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-037", genre: "testing", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-test9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST9, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The line 'I am the means by which her absence gardens' most nearly means that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the garden has died now that she is gone", "the speaker enacts the dead woman's will, so her absence keeps shaping the garden through him", "the speaker gardens in order to forget her", "her absence is itself, literally, tending the plants"], answer: 1, explanation: "He carries out the choices she would have made, so it is through his hands that her not-being-there continues to garden. The died option contradicts a bed that still obeys and blooms. The forget option reverses the poem's fidelity. The literal option misses that 'absence gardens' works only because he is the means.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-038", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST9, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The speaker's letting one weed 'grow on a week beyond its sentence' chiefly expresses...", format: "single_best", options: ["ordinary neglect of his duties", "resentment toward the dead woman", "an impulse to let the garden live by its own nature rather than the fixed plan", "a wish to let the garden fall into ruin"], answer: 2, explanation: "The 'small mutiny of green' lets the plot do something she would not have chosen, a deliberate gesture toward life over the imposed shape. The neglect option misreads a conscious act as carelessness. The resentment option overstates a quiet ambivalence. The ruin option exaggerates one tolerated weed into destruction.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-039", genre: "testing", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-test9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST9, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The attitude toward preserving expressed in the final lines is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["confident that faithful preservation is a clear duty", "bitter at having been made a servant of the dead", "ambivalent, recognising faithfulness to a fixed shape as a kind of resistance to life", "indifferent to what becomes of the garden"], answer: 2, explanation: "The closing question, whether to preserve is to stand between a thing and the life it wants, holds duty and doubt together without resolving them. The confident option ignores that doubt. The bitter option overstates into grievance. The indifferent option contradicts the evident care in the tending.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-040", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST10, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main contention is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["whatever is natural is generally good and whatever is unnatural is suspect", "whether something is natural does not settle whether it is good, and the defensible version of the appeal is only a narrower caution grounded in our ignorance", "human beings should avoid interfering with the natural world", "modern medicine has proved that nature is mostly cruel"], answer: 1, explanation: "The passage denies that naturalness tracks value, then allows only a modest caution resting on what we do not understand. The first option states the view being refuted. The avoid-interfering option is the reverence the passage separates from caution. The cruelty option overreads the examples into a sweeping verdict on nature.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-041", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST10, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The pairs 'disease... the antibiotic' and 'cruelty between animals... the hospital' are offered to show that...", format: "single_best", options: ["medicine is in every respect superior to nature", "nature is, on the whole, a cruel system", "much of what is natural is bad and much human good is unnatural, so naturalness cannot certify value", "humans should never interfere with natural processes"], answer: 2, explanation: "Each pair sets a natural harm against an unnatural good, breaking the link between natural and good. The superior option overgeneralises beyond the point about value. The cruel-system option fastens on half the examples. The never-interfere option draws the opposite practical moral.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-042", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST10, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The remark that 'Caution is not reverence' draws a line between...", format: "single_best", options: ["cowardice and genuine respect", "prudent humility about what we do not understand and the belief that nature carries moral authority", "scientific thinking and religious thinking", "people who are careful and people who are careless"], answer: 1, explanation: "Caution rests on ignorance, reverence on nature's supposed authority, so the line separates the prudent from the worshipper. The cowardice option misreads caution as fear. The science-religion option is broader than the contrast drawn. The careful-careless option loses the point, since both reverent and prudent people may be careful.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-043", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST10, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrower claim is said to 'cut both ways' because the same humility that warns against altering nature also...", format: "single_best", options: ["can be used to win any argument whatever", "warns against assuming that what is customary is therefore sound", "turns out to refute itself on inspection", "ends up supporting reverence for nature after all"], answer: 1, explanation: "Humility about limited understanding distrusts both meddling with ecosystems and complacency about inherited custom, so it disturbs the traditionalist too. The any-argument option overstates into uselessness. The self-refuting option is not claimed. The supports-reverence option is exactly what the passage denies, since caution is not reverence.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-044", genre: "testing", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-test11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST11, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Aunt Vera is best understood as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a cruel woman who actively wishes her nieces ill", "a wise truth-teller who is unfairly resented", "someone whose candour gratifies herself more than it helps those it targets", "a shy woman who finds it hard to communicate"], answer: 2, explanation: "The passage locates her pleasure in seeing clearly and saying so, distinct from any wish to cure. The cruel option overstates, since she means no harm and simply enjoys being right. The wise-and-resented option adopts her own flattering self-image. The shy option contradicts her unasked generosity with advice.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-045", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST11, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of truth as 'a parcel one was obliged to accept on delivery' conveys that Vera assumes...", format: "single_best", options: ["her unflattering truths must be received simply because they are true", "she gives generous material gifts to her nieces", "the truth is always a burden to those who hear it", "people ought to be more grateful than they are"], answer: 0, explanation: "The parcel one must accept figures her belief that a true judgement carries an obligation to take it, however it lands. The material-gifts option literalises the parcel. The burden option is closer to the recipients' experience than to Vera's assumption. The grateful option is a complaint the passage does not put in her mouth as her premise.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-046", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST11, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The observation that 'the relish with which she diagnosed the failings of her nieces was not quite the same thing as a wish to cure them' implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["Vera was a genuinely skilled diagnostician of character", "Vera secretly hated her nieces", "her enjoyment of being right is distinct from, and may crowd out, any real concern for their improvement", "she wished to help but simply lacked tact"], answer: 2, explanation: "Relish in diagnosis is set against the wish to cure, suggesting the pleasure, not the helping, is the point. The skilled option takes diagnosed at face value. The hated option overstates indifference into malice. The lacked-tact option is the charitable reading the sentence is designed to withhold.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-047", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST12, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main point is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["criticism is a more effective teaching tool than praise", "the apparent effects of praise and criticism are largely a statistical artefact, not evidence about feedback", "flight instructors should give less feedback to cadets", "luck plays no real part in a cadet's performance"], answer: 1, explanation: "The swings after praise and criticism are explained as regression from extreme performances, so they say little about the feedback itself. The criticism option is the instructor's mistaken conclusion. The less-feedback option is advice the passage does not give. The no-luck option contradicts the very mechanism invoked.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-048", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST12, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The pattern would appear 'even if his words made no difference at all' because...", format: "single_best", options: ["the cadets ignore whatever the instructor says", "praise and criticism happen to cancel each other out", "extreme performances are partly luck and tend to be followed by more average ones regardless of feedback", "the instructor measures the landings incorrectly"], answer: 2, explanation: "An exceptional landing is partly chance and the next tends back toward the cadet's norm, producing the swing with or without comment. The ignore option posits an inattention the passage never mentions. The cancel option misdescribes the mechanism. The mismeasure option blames measurement error, but the artefact arises from real, fluctuating performance measured at its extremes.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-049", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST12, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The instructor's central error is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["praising cadets too rarely", "treating a regression effect as a causal one, reading the natural return toward average as the work of his words", "failing to keep proper records of each landing", "being harsher with cadets than he ought to be"], answer: 1, explanation: "He mistakes a statistical return toward the mean for the causal power of praise and criticism. The too-rarely option concerns frequency, not his reasoning. The records option is irrelevant to the inference. The harsher option is a moral complaint, not the logical mistake the passage identifies.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-050", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST13, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem is chiefly about...", format: "single_best", options: ["the speaker's anger at being left no money or property", "an inherited habit of damaging silence that the speaker is unknowingly passing on", "the speaker's deep and uncomplicated love for his father", "the difficulty of writing a fitting eulogy"], answer: 1, explanation: "The only bequest is a learned withholding of the needed word, which the close shows being handed on in turn. The anger option misreads the list of what was not left as grievance about money. The love option ignores the poem's unease. The eulogy option seizes on the wreath but misses the inheritance theme.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-051", genre: "testing", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-test13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST13, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "Calling the silence 'the one estate he could be certain to bequeath' figures it as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a large property the father in fact owned", "the only sure inheritance, his learned reticence cast as the true thing handed down", "something as financially valuable as land would be", "a gift the father consciously intended to pass on"], answer: 1, explanation: "Estate makes the reticence the real legacy, the one thing certainly transmitted. The property option literalises the metaphor. The value option imports a comparison of worth the poem does not press. The intended option contradicts 'without quite meaning to', which makes the transmission unwitting.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-052", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST13, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The final image, the silence 'passed along / intact, to those who stand and grieve beneath', most strongly implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the family has openly reconciled its differences", "the speaker has broken the cycle of silence", "the speaker is transmitting the same silence to the next generation, so the pattern continues", "the mourners deeply admired the dead father"], answer: 2, explanation: "Passing the silence on intact to those grieving beneath shows the habit reproduced in the next generation. The reconciled option contradicts a legacy of withheld words. The broken-cycle option is the opposite of intact. The admired option reads the grief as praise the poem does not give.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-053", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST14, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main contention is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["consistency is the most important intellectual virtue", "consistency is only the agreement of beliefs with one another, not with the truth, so it is no guarantee of being right and can obstruct correction", "people should change their views as often as possible", "open-minded people are usually wrong"], answer: 1, explanation: "Consistency is internal agreement, compatible with being wholly mistaken, and over-prizing it blocks revision. The most-important option is the view under attack. The change-often option mistakes responsiveness for restlessness. The usually-wrong option misreads the praise of the open mind.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-054", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST14, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The examples of the miser and the fanatic are used to show that...", format: "single_best", options: ["misers and fanatics are unusually logical people", "one can be flawlessly consistent while being wrong, so consistency by itself is no merit", "inconsistency is always preferable to consistency", "consistency tends to cause fanaticism"], answer: 1, explanation: "Both are models of internal consistency yet hardly models of truth, which is the point. The logical option flatters them beyond the argument. The always-preferable option overstates, since the passage values responsiveness to evidence, not inconsistency for its own sake. The causes option asserts a causal link the passage does not claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-055", genre: "testing", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-test15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST15, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The manager's 'frankness' is best described as...", format: "single_best", options: ["a consistent commitment to plain speaking with everyone", "candour directed only at subordinates, while he stays cautious and evasive with superiors, so his honesty tracks safety rather than principle", "an admirable courage that his staff fail to appreciate", "an inability to control his temper under pressure"], answer: 1, explanation: "He is plain only downward and all nuance upward, so the honesty follows wherever it is safe. The consistent option is contradicted by the asymmetry. The courage option inverts a self-serving habit into a virtue. The temper option imports an emotional failing the passage does not describe.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-056", genre: "testing", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-test15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST15, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The weather image, honesty blowing 'from the regions of low pressure toward the high, and never the other way', means that...", format: "single_best", options: ["his moods were as unpredictable as the weather", "his candour always flowed downward, to those beneath him in power, and never upward", "he remained calm under pressure", "honesty is, like weather, a natural and impersonal force"], answer: 1, explanation: "Low to high and never the reverse maps candour travelling only down the hierarchy, never up to his superiors. The moods option seizes on weather but ignores the fixed direction. The calm option misreads pressure as stress. The natural-force option turns a pointed metaphor into a vague generality.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-057", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST16, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The discovery that the script's margins were 'unmarked, as though there had been nothing to decide' most strongly suggests...", format: "single_best", options: ["the understudy had never actually learned the part", "a readiness so complete, or a resignation so deep, that the question of interpretation no longer arose for him", "the understudy disliked the play he was cast in", "the script was only a spare copy he never used"], answer: 1, explanation: "The poem explicitly hovers between discipline and a long despair, so the blank margins read as either total readiness or deep resignation. The never-learned option contradicts knowing the part by heart. The disliked option invents a feeling the poem withholds. The spare-copy option ignores 'his only script'.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-058", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST16, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The closing phrase that he 'had become the role by playing air' implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["he literally performed in empty theatres", "by rehearsing a part he never performed, he came to embody it in absence, living the understudy's role itself", "he had entirely forgotten who he was", "his talent had been completely wasted"], answer: 1, explanation: "Playing to no audience for thirty years, he is absorbed into the part precisely by never getting to play it, so absence becomes his role. The literal option misreads 'air'. The forgotten option overstates into loss of identity. The wasted option is a tempting moral, but the poem leaves the value of his life deliberately open rather than declaring it waste.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-059", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test17", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST17, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central point is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the charity is probably lying about its results", "the ninety per cent figure cannot be interpreted without a comparison group, so it does not show the charity caused the recovery", "ninety per cent is too low a success rate to be impressive", "charities should never report statistics to donors"], answer: 1, explanation: "Without knowing how similar families fare unaided, the figure cannot be credited to the charity. The lying option misses that the number may be true yet meaningless. The too-low option misjudges the rhetorical problem. The never-report option is broader than the passage's specific complaint.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-060", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test17", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST17, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The figure is called 'a number in search of a meaning' because...", format: "single_best", options: ["the figure is most likely false", "ninety per cent is not a large enough proportion to matter", "without the recovery rate of comparable families given no help, the result cannot be attributed to the charity", "charities should not be allowed to use percentages"], answer: 2, explanation: "It lacks the baseline that would let us tell help from the ordinary action of time, so its meaning is missing. The false option swaps truth for interpretability. The not-large option misreads the size of the number as the issue. The not-allowed option is a rule the passage does not propose.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-061", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST18, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The two senses of 'deserve' the passage distinguishes are...", format: "single_best", options: ["a legal sense and a moral sense", "one that rewards the effort a person made, and one that questions whether the conditions for that effort were themselves earned", "a sincere sense and a cynical sense", "a sense about money and a sense about social status"], answer: 1, explanation: "One sense credits effort, the other audits the unearned advantages that made the effort possible. The legal-moral option imposes a distinction the passage never names. The sincere-cynical option treats the two sides as honest versus dishonest, whereas the passage says both are partly right. The money-status option narrows the rewards to a kind the text does not specify.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-062", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST18, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Describing the quarrel as 'not a disagreement so much as a collision' implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the dispute is unusually bitter and personal", "the parties are not contradicting each other but using one word for two different things, so they talk past one another", "one of the two sides must be lying", "the question of desert has no possible answer"], answer: 1, explanation: "A collision rather than a disagreement marks two parties whose claims never meet because deserve means something different in each mouth. The bitter option reads collision as hostility. The lying option ignores that both are right about what they assert. The no-answer option overstates, since the trouble is equivocation, not unanswerability.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-063", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test19", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST19, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage suggests that the village's much-admired 'spirit' was...", format: "single_best", options: ["entirely manufactured for the newspapers", "genuine, yet mixed with relief at a disaster large enough to dwarf and excuse their petty grievances", "pure and uncomplicated heroism", "secretly resented by everyone involved"], answer: 1, explanation: "The embraces were not lies, but the warmth was partly the relief of meannesses made to look small, so genuine feeling and self-serving relief mix. The manufactured option contradicts 'not lying'. The pure option ignores the buried unkindnesses. The resented option overstates into universal bad faith.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-064", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test19", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST19, attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The final image of 'water that would, in time, go down' implies that...", format: "single_best", options: ["the physical flood damage would eventually be repaired", "the buried grievances are only submerged, not resolved, and may resurface when normal life returns", "the village would soon forget the flood entirely", "another flood was likely to come in future"], answer: 1, explanation: "If the water that buried the quarrels recedes, what it covered will reappear, so the grievances are hidden rather than healed. The damage option literalises the receding water. The forget option reverses the implication that the troubles return. The another-flood option predicts a new event rather than the resurfacing of the old grievances.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-065", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test20", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST20, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem's central idea is that...", format: "single_best", options: ["collecting butterflies is a cruel and expensive pastime", "to possess something by fixing it is to lose the very life that made it worth having", "the collector should have gathered even more specimens", "butterflies are most beautiful when seen behind glass"], answer: 1, explanation: "Having the colours but not the flight shows that fixing the thing destroys what made it valuable. The cruel-and-expensive option moralises about the hobby rather than stating the theme. The more-specimens option misses that quantity is exactly the failure. The behind-glass option praises the very stillness the poem laments.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-066", genre: "testing", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-test20", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: TST20, attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The closing lines, that he 'owned a hundred specimens of blue / and not one living instance of the blue', chiefly mean that...", format: "single_best", options: ["he owned many butterflies but always wanted still more", "he possessed the colour only as a dead specimen, never as a living, moving reality", "the butterflies he collected were of an especially rare colour", "collecting had become an expensive obsession for him"], answer: 1, explanation: "A hundred dead specimens of blue, but no living blue, contrasts the captured colour with the life that has fled it. The wanted-more option imports a greed not in these lines. The rare-colour option fastens on blue as rarity. The expensive option repeats a money theme the poem does not raise.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
];

